running, the 34-year-old Briton's bid for a fifth straight global 10,000/5,000m double was scuppered as he had to settle for the silver\n\nMo Farah's aura of invincibility after six years of unrelenting success was finally cracked in his very last major track race on Saturday as he lost his world 5,000 meters title to Ethiopia's Muktar Edris.\n\nSeeking a fitting end to his matchless long-distance racing career before moving to marathon running, the 34-year-old Briton's bid for a fifth straight global 10,000/5,000m double was scuppered as he had to settle for the silver.\n\nYet even in defeat, Farah demonstrated his champion's spirit as he fought back in the dying meters when it looked as if he would be shut out of the medals completely.\n\nIn a thrilling final featuring four athletes careering towards the line, Farah snatched back second place behind Edris, who clocked 13 minutes 32.79 seconds after a searing final lap of 52.6 seconds.\n\n\"I gave it all but I had nothing left at the end,\" a crestfallen and emotional Farah said.\n\n\"It's been a long journey but it's been incredible. It doesn't quite sink in until you compete here and cross the line - I had a couple of minutes to myself - that this is it.\n\n\"To be honest with you, it takes so much out of me.\n\n\"It's not an excuse, but it took a lot more out of me than I realized.\"\n\nIt was a glorious win for 23-year-old Ethiopian Edris, the fastest man in the world this year, who had lost all his five previous meetings with Farah.\n\nYet just like Usain Bolt in the 100 meters the previous weekend, it did look a race too far for the weary Briton.\n\nTo rub in his victory after years of the Ethiopians being tormented by Farah's brilliance, Edris even gave an impression of his rival's famed \"Mobot\" celebration as he crossed the line.\n\n\"I was highly prepared for this race and I knew I was going to beat Mo Farah,\" Edris said.\n\n\"After the 10km he was maybe tired so he did not have enough for the last kick. I was stronger.\n\n\"I didn't have much support but we did it. I did the Mobot out of respect as well for him.\"\n\nBehind Edris, Farah dug deep to battle back from fourth to second when space opened up on the inside over the last few meters to take silver in 13:33.22.", "time": "11:36:00"}

column inches.\n\nThe 34-year-old saw his global championship win streak of 10 gold medals dating back to the 5,000m at the 2011 world championships ended as Muktar Edris of Ethiopia held off his throat as the 5,000m runners lined up before their race.\n\n\"It is what it is, I just meant that I was going to take Mo down,\" said Chelimo.\n\nThe Observer remarked that those who had come in their thousands with their faces painted with \"Go Mo!\" and banners with \"Run Farah Run\" were to be left disappointed.\n\nIt also commented on how his soon to turn five twin daughters Aisha and Amani had never seen him lose a major final before Saturday.\n\n\"He curled into the foetal position at the finish, beaten in a major final for the first time in six years,\" wrote the correspondent.\n\n\"Silver on this occasion stung like defeat and salt was rubbed into open wounds by his conqueror, Muktar Edris of Ethiopia, performing the iconic Mobot at the finish.\"\n\n(This British Olympic star shockingly finished second in his last on-the-track IAAF World Outdoor Track & Field Championship race, a 5,000 meters on Saturday.\n\nBoxed in at one point, he had to dig deep in the final meters just to earn a medal, running 13 minutes, 33.22 seconds in a slow race that was almost a minute off the world record.\n\nThe gold went to former world junior champion Mukta Edris of Ethiopia in 13:32.79 with U.S. Olympic silver medalist Paul Chelimo claiming the bronze in 13:33.30.\n\n\"I gave it everything,\" said Farah, who is moving up to the marathon.\n\nThe double Olympic champion in the 5,000 and 10,000 meters, he was chasing his fourth world title in the 5,000 after winning the 10,000 meters on the opening night of the championships.\n\nBut on the final lap, Ethiopia's Yomif Kejelcha, the world indoor 3,000 winner at Portland last year, accelerated to the front.\n\nEdris held second and Farah third with Chelimo joining the mix before Edris surged to the lead down the straight.\n\nFarah somehow found a bit of room on the inside of Kejelcha and Chelimo and, giving his all, the Nike Oregon Project runner managed to snatch the silver with Edris, whose closing speed was always going to be a threat, the clear winner.\n\n\"I thought it might be possible, but my legs had it,\" Farah said of the closing chase for gold.\n\n\"I got boxed in early on -- it doesn't normally happen -- but I got boxed in early and couldn't get out.\"\n\nEven before then, the race had been taxing, Farah said.\n\n\"It took a lot more out of me than I realized,\" he said. \"Tactically, I was trying to cover every move. They (the Ethiopians) had the game plan: one of them was going to sacrifice themselves.\n\n\"That's what they did tonight, and the better man won on the day. I gave it all, I didn't have a single bit left at the end.\"\n\nA confident Edris said he and the Ethiopians were prepared for Farah this time.\n\n\"I knew I was going to beat Mo Farah,\" the new gold medalist said. \"After the (10,000) he was maybe tired so he did not have enough for the last kick. I was stronger.\"\n\nAfterward Edris did the Mobot, Farah's signature postrace move, to celebrate his win and out of respect for Farah.\n\n\"Mo has many victories but now I have one,\" Edris said. \"I am the new champion for Ethiopia. That's why I did the Mobot. I am the next champion.\"\n\nPortland's Mohammed Ahmed of the Bowerman Track Club was sixth in 13:35.43 for Canada.\n\nIllness prevented Ryan Hill, also of Portland and the Bowerman Track Club, from running the final.\n\nWhile his sickness is not believed to be related to the norovirus outbreak affecting athletes at the championships, doctors advised him not to compete after an examination on Saturday, USA Track & Field said.\n\nThe U.S. women won the 4x100 relay gold in the year's fastest time, 41.82 seconds.\n\nAaliyah Brown, Allyson Felix, Morolake Akinosun and Tori Bowie combined for the women's victory.\n\nUO's Ariana Washington helped set up the win by anchoring the U.S. victory in the morning heats as Bowie rested. Washington will get a gold medal.\n\n\"The aim is gold. we have some great competitors in the back ready to come out here and produce,\" said Washington, her prediction coming true in the final.", "time": "06:47:00"}

DANIEL LEAL-OLIVAS / AFP\n\nBritish athletics legend Mo Farah was hailed by the British press on Sunday despite his glorious track career ending with defeat in the 5,000 metres world championships final.\n\nAlthough his silver medal performance was pushed out of the limelight by the drama of the men's 4x100m relay, which saw fellow legend Usain Bolt collapse with cramp on his own swansong as Britain pulled off a remarkable victory, as well as the thrilling opening of the Premier League season, Farah still commanded many column inches.\n\nThe 34-year-old saw his global championship win streak of 10 gold medals dating back to the 5,000m at the 2011 world championships ended as Muktar Edris of Ethiopia held off his desperate charge in the finishing straight.\n\n\"End of the track for Mo\" headlined The Sunday Times, adding that it was a \"shattering defeat in front of an adoring crowd\".\n\nHowever, the paper eulogised about the performance by Farah -- who came to Britain with his mother and two of his brothers from Somalia via a spell with his grandparents in Djibouti aged just eight -- in the stadium where he had memorably achieved his first Olympic double in 2012.\n\n\"If defeat is the making of a true champion, then Mo Farah left the track at the Olympic stadium last night as the greatest champion of all,\" wrote its sports writer.\n\n\"That he failed, beaten finally, for the first time at a major championships since 2011, by Muktar Edris of Ethiopia, stripped nothing from the legend.\"\n\nThe Sun on Sunday, never one to miss out on an eye-catching pun, perhaps unkindly went with \"Slow Mo\".\n\nHowever, Farah -- who has had a tense relationship with large sections of the British media over the questions raised by his loyalty to controversial United States-based coach Alberto Salazar -- would have been happier with what followed.\n\n\"The 34-year-old is hanging up his spikes to take to the roads in the marathon after a stellar career which has seen him establish himself as one of the all-time greats of the sport,\" purred the Sun correspondent.\n\n\"Yet despite the huge support from the home crowd packed into the London Stadium, Britain's hero was finally knocked off his perch as the king of long-distance running.\"\n\n'I was going to take Mo down'\n\nThe Mail On Sunday headlined their tale of Farah's final bow \"Oh Mo!\"\n\nThey called it a \"disappointing silver\" but pointed to the remarkable career of Britain's most successful ever athlete.\n\nAnd they took aim at America's Kenyan-born bronze medallist Richard Chelimo for making Farah's trademark 'Mobot' gesture and then running his hand across his throat as the 5,000m runners lined up before their race.\n\n\"It is what it is, I just meant that I was going to take Mo down,\" said Chelimo.\n\nThe Observer remarked that those who had come in their thousands with their faces painted with \"Go Mo!\" and banners with \"Run Farah Run\" were to be left disappointed.\n\nIt also commented on how his soon to turn five twin daughters Aisha and Amani had never seen him lose a major final before Saturday.\n\n\"He curled into the foetal position at the finish, beaten in a major final for the first time in six years,\" wrote the correspondent.\n\n\"Silver on this occasion stung like defeat and salt was rubbed into open wounds by his conqueror, Muktar month.\n\n\"I'm going to do it. "http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/sad-endings-for-bolt-farah-at-world-athletics-championships-roundup-117081300383_1.html", "body": "The World Athletics Championships just can't stop popping up surprises even as Jamaican great Usain Bolt and local hero Mohamed Farah bid farewell to their respective careers amid tears and defeat.\n\nIn the last race of his career, Bolt limped off the track while hosts Britain took the stunning 4x100m victory to the ecstacy of the capacity London Stadium spectators here on Saturday evening, reports Xinhua news agency.\n\nBolt, running the anchor leg, staggered halfway down the straight, dropping the baton before falling facing down. Dreaming of hanging up his running spikes without a defeat in a major championship, the 11-time world champion and eight-time Olympic titlist limped across the finish line.\n\nBolt had only taken a few strides when he appeared to suffer an injury to his left leg and fell to the track in pain. He stayed down for a couple of minutes before standing up and walking to the finish line.\n\nBritain won the gold in 37.47 seconds, the US took silver in 37.52 and Japan was third in 38.04. China, the silver medalist two years ago, finished fourth in 38.34 with second-leg runner Xie Zhenye just coming back from injury.\n\nThe British team of Chijindu Ujah, Adam Gemili, Danny Talbot and Nethaneel Mitchell-Blake broke the European record that had stood since 1999 by 0.26 seconds. That record was established by the British team of Jason Gardener, Darren Campbell, Marlon Devonish and Dwain Chambers as silver medal winners behind the USA at the 1999 IAAF World Championships in Seville, Spain.\n\nBritish anchor runner Nethaneel Michell-Blake dropped to the ground in blissful disbelief as his team beat the American squad consisting of newly crowned 100m world champion Justin Gatlin and runner-up Christian Coleman.\n\nIt brought back memories of the Athens Olympics in 2004, when Mark Lewis-Francis held off Maurice Greene to claim an unlikely Olympic victory over the Americans. The only other global senior championship success for Britain in the men's 4x100m relay was at the 1912 Olympics in Stockholm.\n\nIt was a rollercoaster night for the celebrating home fans when a couple of hours ago their emotion could only be described as disappointed when Farah failed in his quest for a fourth 5,000m world title in his farewell race just like Bolt.\n\nYoung Ethiopian star Muktar Edris has beaten the all-dominating Mohamed Farah of Britain to win the men's 5,000 metre title at the IAAF World Championships here.\n\nEdris, who was crowned world youth champion in 2012, produced a strong charge on the final stretch to register a time of 13 minutes and 32.79 seconds on Saturday evening, Xinhua news agency reported.\n\nThe 23-year-old, who won the first major senior world title of his career, stopped Farah from taking his fourth 5,000m world title.\n\nThe Somali-origin Farah has won Olympic gold in the men's 5,000m twice and has won the men's 10,000m title at this event.\n\nHowever on Saturday night, Farah had to be content with the second place after finishing with a time of 13:33.22. Paul Kipkemoi Chelimo of the US took bronze in 13:33.30. Farah, who was surrounded by Ethiopean runners going into the final stages of the race, produced a desperate final sprint but failed to catch up with the leader.\n\n\"I gave it everything,\" said Farah who initially curled up on the track in defeat and then was pulled up by Edris.\n\nJust like Jamaican great Usain Bolt, Farah finished his career with an unusual feeling of defeat.\n\nThe 34-year-old had won this event in the past three world championships and two Olympic Games, together with three world titles and two Olympic gold medals in 10,000m.\n\nHowever, he remains hero of the country, bagging one gold and one silver in London, which are the only medals the hosts have won by far.\n\nFarah, who had said this would be his last World Championships, will now turn his focus to marathon running.\n\nWhile Farah handed over his long distance crown, the next generation of Ethiopian runners announced their arrival on the world stage.\n\nEdris' fellow Ethiopians 2016 world indoor champion Yomif Kejelcha, 21, and this year's U-18 3,000m winner Selemon Barega were placed fourth and fifth respectively, indicating that the east Africans will continue to be a force to reckon at the international level.\n\nA surprise also took place in the field events as Johannes Vetter of Germany grabbed his first ever medal at a major global competition -- a golden one -- with his first attempt of 89.89 meters to win the men's javelin event even as defending champion Julius Yego and Olympic champion Thomas Rohler failed to deliver.\n\nJakub Vadlejch of Czech Republic finished second in 89.73m ahead of compatriot Petr Frydrych who registered 88.32m.\n\nRohler, from Germany, made a 88.26m throw in his second attempt and finished fourth while defending champion Julius Yego of Kenya was eliminated after the first three rounds.\n\nIn other events, Russia's Maria Lasitskene retained the women's high jump title.\n\nThe 24-year-old, competing as an authorized neutral athlete, cleared 2.03 meters for the gold medal. Ukraine's Yuliia Levchenko took silver in 2.01 and Poland's Kamila Licwinko was third in 1.99.\n\nLasitskene, who missed last year's Rio Olympics because of Russia's suspension, failed at 1.99 twice but regained form thereafter.\n\n\"My two failed attempts at 1.99m woke me up,\" she said.\n\n\"A gold medal here was my main goal for this season but certainly I would like to raise the bar a bit higher. I didn't like any one of my attempts at 2.08m.\"\n\nShe challenged 2.08 three times but failed.\n\n\"It was an unbelievable championships for me. I was focussed from the opening jump until the last attempt. I didn't allow myself to get emotional,\" Levchenko said.\n\n\"At 2.01m it was not my best technical attempt. I thought that such a height would not forgive the mistakes I made.\"\n\nMeanwhile, USA regained the women's 4x100m world crown which they last won at the 2011 World Championships in Daegu as they sailed to victory in 41.82 seconds while hosts Britain gladly bagged a silver in 42.12. Defending champions Jamaica clocked 42.19 for the bronze.\n\nAustralia's Sally Pearson won her second world women's 100 meters hurdles title in six years.\n\nPearson, 30, who won the world title in 2011 and Olympic gold five years ago, clocked 12.59 seconds for the gold. American Dawn Harper Nelson, who won the Olympic gold in Beijing and silver in London behind Pearson, took silver in 12.63 seconds. Germany's Pamela Dutkiewicz finished third in 12.72 seconds.\n\n\"It's been a long journey back from injury but to get this moment and go and celebrate in front of my family is unreal. This is just so incredible to be a world champion again,\" Pearson, also the silver medallist in the Beijing Olympics, said.\n\n\"I love this stadium. I love the people and I'm so happy to have been back here doing the same thing again (winning gold). It's a relief to be world champion.\"\n\nRio Olympic silver medalist Kevin Mayer claimed France's second gold from the men's decathlon with a total of 8,768 points. Germany's Rico Freimuth, bronze winner two years ago in the Beijing worlds, took silver in 8,564 points and his compatriot Kai Kazmirek got the bronze in 8,488.\n\n(This story has not been edited by Business Standard staff and is auto-generated from a syndicated feed.)", "time": "11:15:00"}

missing out on a fairytale finale at the World Championships.\n\nThe four-time Olympic champion failed to mount a third defence of his 5,000m title as Ethiopia's Muktar Edris claimed gold in London on Saturday.\n\nFarah, who had already won the 10,000m last week, had not lost a final in 2,176 days.\n\nThe 34-year-old collapsed to the track after the race and covered his face before being hauled to his feet.\n\nHe is due to retire from the track at the end of the month, after the Diamond League final in Zurich, to focus on the marathon, and conceded he was overcome in the London Stadium.\n\nHe said: \"I had tears in my eyes, I've never had that before. It's been an amazing journey. To end it in London, where it all started, I got a bit emotional.\n\n\"I look at my family, what I've done and it gets to you. At the end of the day I'm human and it hasn't all been a smooth ride.\n\n\"If I had it perfect it would have been nice to end in double double but anything is possible. At some point it has to come to an end.\n\n\"I always told myself London is where it started and London was where it was going to stop. I was known as normal Mo and then overnight after London I was 'Mo', I couldn't go anywhere. To finish here is a nice thing.\n\n\"I know myself when I crossed the line there was nothing left of me, nothing. I gave my all. Over the years it has worked and I crossed the line first, but not tonight.\"\n\nFarah won the 10,000m and 5,000m at the 2013 and 2015 World Championships while he also claimed the 5,000m crown in 2011, taking silver in the 10,000m - the last time he was beaten.\n\nHe crossed the line in 13 minutes 33.22 seconds but was defeated after failing to mount a recovery in the last 200m in a frantic sprint finish.\n\nEdris finished in 13mins 32.79secs, with the United States' Paul Chelimo third.\n\nEdris did the 'Mobot' - Farah's trademark celebration - soon after crossing the line but Farah dismissed any suggestions it was a taunt in his own back yard.\n\n\"These guys all respect me and the reason why he did that is they respect me for what I've done for the sport,\" he said.\n\n\"It's no secret to what we do. These guys have seen me year after year and to be able to have that long career and keep coming back.\n\n\"I have to give credit to Edris. The Ethiopians had a game plan and they had to sacrifice one, Yomif Kejelcha, to get a medal so Edris could sit at the back and do as little work as possible and to beat me on the last lap.\"\n\nFarah runs in Birmingham in the Diamond League next Sunday before finishing in Zurich and is now eager to start a new era on the road.\n\nHe said: \"In terms of my chapter of my life I wanted to close here. I've got races in Birmingham and Zurich but it doesn't really matter. In terms of major championships I'm done, that chapter of my life is closed and I want to start a new one and move on to the roads.\n\n\"If you look at the history, it doesn't lie. What I've achieved has been incredible. I know I gave it all, the better man won on the day. It's a matter of staying hungry, motivated and for me to start a new challenge.\n\n\"I've seen a lot of great athletes go to the road and run decent times.\"\n\nBritish team-mate Andrew Butchart finished eighth in 13mins 38.73secs.\n\nMeanwhile, Katarina Johnson-Thompson and Morgan Lake finished fifth and sixth respectively in the women's high jump.\n\nThey both failed to clear 1.97 metres - just one centimetre short of Johnson-Thompson's personal best - having jumped 1.95m and Ashley Bryant came 11th in the decathlon with 8,049 points.\n\nAP", "time": "08:58:00"}

"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mo_Farah", "label": {"eng": "Mo Farah"}, "score": 3, "type": "person", "id": "338647"}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scuttlebutt", "label": {"eng": "Scuttlebutt"}, "score": 3, "type": "wiki", "id": "356648"}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alberto_Salazar", "label": {"eng": "Alberto Salazar"}, "score": 2, "type": "person", "id": "366378"}, "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2011_World_Championships_in_Athletics", "label": {"eng": "2011 World Championships in Athletics"}, "score": 2, "type": "wiki", "id": "456501"}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Panorama_(TV_series)", "label": {"eng": "Panorama (TV series)"}, "score": 2, "type": "wiki", "id": "460671"}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tim_Montgomery", "label": {"eng": "Tim Montgomery"}, "score": 3, "type": "person", "id": "539921"}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ross_Tucker", "label": {"eng": "Ross Tucker"}, "score": 2, "type": "person", "id": "568360"}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Victor_Conte", "label": {"eng": "Victor Conte"}, "score": 3, "type": "person", "id": "597775"}], "url": "http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/aug/11/mo-farah-track-legacy-world-athletics-championships", "body": "When Farah competes in his last major track race, at the world championships on Saturday, the support in the London Stadium will be deafening. But away from the roars of adoration, his career still invites scrutiny and suspicion\n\nInside the London Stadium they have nothing but love for Mo Farah. On Saturday night Farah will race on the track there for the last time, in the 5,000m final, and whether he wins gold or not, the home fans will cheer every stride he takes. Here - where every roar carries an echo of 2012 - watching Farah run remains a straightforward pleasure, one people will pay a lot of money to experience. It is beyond the stadium walls that everything gets more complicated. Because out there, not everyone is applauding. As Farah winds down his track career, his legacy and reputation have come to look as knotty and complicated as the tangled girders of the Orbit.\n\nIn 2014, the website Letsrun.com ran a \"doping perception poll\". It was designed to show whether their readers perceived athletes to be \"clean\" or \"dirty\". A lot of elite athletes (and their agents) hate Letsrun. It is the place where running junkies go to talk about the sport, and its message boards are filled with anonymous commentators sharing scurrilous accusations and scuttlebutt. They are a cynical lot. But then a lot of athletics fans are, because they have been lied to so many times - by Ben Johnson, Marion Jones, Tim Montgomery and all the other athletes who were caught doping.\n\nFarah was one of the athletes Letsrun asked people to vote on. Of the 5,584 people who did, 56% thought he was \"clean\" and 44% thought he was \"dirty\". Compare that to the polls for the two other great long distance runners of the modern era, Haile Gebrselassie and Kenenisa Bekele. Gebrselassie's split was 73% \"clean\" to 27% \"dirty\" and Bekele's 72% to 28%. Which does not mean Farah is doping, just that a lot of Letsrun's readers think he is. And that is true in Britain too. Letsrun broke the results down by country. Among the 270 British voters, 64% thought Farah was clean, 36% did not.\n\nFarah has never failed a drugs test, a fact he has repeated again and again. The trouble is, a lot of athletes who later admitted to doping used to say that too. Marion Jones passed 160 tests in a row (though she did eventually fail one, in 2006) and used that very argument when she sued Victor Conte for defamation because he said he had seen her take human growth hormone. They settled out of court. The IAAF's anti-doping programme was so flawed for so long that every competitor has been compromised. After Lance Armstrong, a lot of sports fans feel that passing tests is not a defence that passes muster.\n\nThat is not Farah's fault but it is his problem. Because, hard as this is for his many fans to hear, his career invites scrutiny. To understand why, you need to go back a decade, to 2007. That year Farah set a personal best of 13min 7sec. That ranks, now, just within the thousand fastest times ever run. There is no hard rule about when a distance runner reaches his peak but a study of 72 elite 5,000m runners published in 2011 found that the mean average age for the peak performance in that group was 24 years old. Which is the age Farah was when he ran that PB.\n\nAt the world championships in Osaka that year Farah finished sixth in the 5,000m. At the world championships in Berlin in the 2009 he finished seventh. By then he was 26. It is hard for an athlete to make a leap forward at that age but Farah did. In 2010, when he was 27, Farah lowered his PB by 9.6sec and then in 2011, when he was 28, he cut it again by another 4.83sec. He explained the biggest reason for the improvements was that he had spent his winters training in Kenya and Ethiopia. It was also said he had become a lot more disciplined in his training and more dedicated to his career.\n\nBy then Farah had also joined Nike's Oregon Project and started working under Alberto Salazar. \"I believe he can just make that half per cent difference to get close to a medal,\" he explained. Salazar did more than that. He turned Farah from the best distance runner in Britain into the best distance runner in the world. Farah won his first world championship title at Daegu in 2011, in the 5,000m. There was a lot of talk about the biomechanical changes Salazar had made to Farah's technique, especially for his last lap sprints, and the advanced machinery Farah was now using in training: underwater treadmills, cryogenic chambers and the like.\n\nThere was less discussion of Salazar's medical and supplementation programmes. The details of those started to come out only in 2015, when ProPublica and BBC Panorama published a joint investigation in which two whistleblowers accused Salazar of experimenting with doping aids and of giving athletes prescription medicines they did not need. Salazar and the Oregon Project are still under investigation by the Unites States Anti-Doping Agency. An interim report, leaked earlier this year, gave an insight into how Salazar seemed to have been pushing the boundaries of what may be considered ethically permissible.\n\nThen in 2016 another coach Jama Aden was arrested in Spain. Police found the banned performance-enhancing drug EPO in the room of one of his athletes. Farah had worked with Aden when he first started training in Kenya and had also visited his training camp in Spain. Aden was described as an \"unofficial facilitator\", whose only job was to hold a stopwatch while Farah ran laps.\n\n\"He's not a close friend of mine,\" Farah said. But in his autobiography, published in 2014, he had said he and Aden \"had known each other for years\" and there are several photos of the two of them together. The apparent inconsistencies were unsettling.\n\nAs the athletics analyst Ross Tucker argues: \"I've seen people saying that Farah can't escape the association but that his legacy would have been much stronger and healthier were it not for Salazar. However, I don't see how that argument even exists. This is a man who midway through his career was working with one of Great Britain's best coaches, and whose ceiling appeared to be finals of major global championships and European success. Whatever has been achieved to earn the legacy [and by medals, it is the greatest track career ever] is the result of Salazar and the training camps and so forth.\" Tucker, a high performance sports science consultant, is hosting the Inside Lane podcast for Runners World during these championships.\n\nAside from Farah's associations with Salazar and Aden, there are other disturbing details. In 2015 it emerged Farah had missed two drugs tests, one in 2010 and another in 2011, which happened, he explained, because he had not heard the testers ringing his doorbell. Earlier this year Farah's biological passport details were leaked to the press. They showed in 2015 Farah's results had been flagged as \"likely doping\" but that, in April 2016, they had been checked and flagged as \"normal with the last sample\". Farah's spokesperson said that \"any suggestion of misconduct is entirely false and seriously misleading. Mo Farah has been subject to many blood tests during his career and has never failed a single one.\"\n\nIt all adds up to a long list of hard questions. Farah says he is sick of answering them. Which is one reason why he made the curious decision to hire Freuds to help manage his PR. Farah has released a limited range of his blood test results for public scrutiny, he has reiterated he is committed to clean sport and, of course, he has passed every test he has ever taken. Aside from formally separating himself from Salazar, he must wonder what more he can do. Because in the past three years, Farah has come under more scrutiny than any other athlete on the circuit and at the end of it, he is still subject to suspicion. Loud as the sound will be when he runs on Saturday, listen harder, outside the stadium, and it may start to sound just a little thin.", "time": "13:15:00"}

event at the 2017 IAAF World Championships at the London Stadium in London on August 12, 2017. Daniel LEAL-OLIVAS / AFP\n\nMo Farah proved mortal just as Usain Bolt a week ago in his last individual race as the British icon was denied a winning farewell to the track by Ethiopia's Muktar Edris on Saturday in the world championship 5,000-metre race.\n\nThe season-leader Edris proved the strongest on the home stretch as he beat Farah, who was urged on by the British home crowd, but finally fell short as he missed out on a fifth and final big distance double.\n\n\"I gave it everything. It has been an incredible journey,\" said Farah, who was roared on by a home crowd of 56,000 and has six golds and two silvers from the worlds as he moves on to the marathon.\n\nBolt last week had to settle for bronze in his last individual race, the 100m. But he the Jamaican could bow out with a record-extending 12th world title by winning another 4x100m relay gold later in the evening.\n\nAustralia's Sally Pearson meanwhile shook off years of injury problems when she stormed to her second world title in the 100 metres hurdles; and top favourite Mariya Lasitskene clinched back-to-back high jump titles to give the Russians competing as neutral athletes a first London gold.\n\nThe day's other medal events are the women's sprint relay, the men's javelin and the women's 4x100m relay.\n\nFarah's famous kick in the last lap worked last week in the 10,000m but not on Saturday as Edris broke early, held him off on the home stretch and beat Farah by .43 of a second with 13 minutes 32.79 seconds, with American Paul Chelimo taking bronze.\n\nEdris is the first man to beat Farah in six years since compatriot Ibrahim Jeilan finished ahead of Farah in the 10,000m at the 2011 worlds.\n\nFarah won the next 10 global races for doubles at the 2012 and 2016 Olympics, and 2013 and 2015 worlds.\n\nThe 2011 world and 2012 Olympic champion Pearson, 30, shot into the lead midway through the hurdles and never looked back for gold in 12.59 seconds.\n\nDawn Harper Nelson of the United States, the 2008 Olympic champion, got silver in 12.63. German Pamela Dutkiewicz was a surprise bronze medallist in 12.72, two-hundredths ahead of world record holder Kendra Harrison of the US.\n\n\"It's been a long journey back from injury, but to get this moment and go and celebrate in front of my family is unreal. This is just so incredible to be a world champion again,\" said Pearson who had missed the 2015 worlds and 2016 Games for injury reasons.\n\nLasitskene has ruled the high jump lately and apart from one miss over 1.99m cleared all heights on her first attempt, winning with 2.03m and then failing three times on a national record 2.08m.\n\nUkraine's Yuliia Lerchenko got silver with 2.01m and Poland's Kamila Licwinko.\n\nIn the day's only preliminaries, the US dominated the women's and men's 4x400m heats into the finals which conclude the championships as part of 11 medal events Sunday.\n\nIn the others, Kenya's Asbel Kiprop seeks a fourth straight 1,500-metre gold; Ethiopian Almaz Ayana to complete a rare women's distance running double in the 5,000m, and Caster Semenya is the top favourite for a second 800m title a year after Olympic gold.\n\nThe women's discus contender and men's high jump are also on the schedule of the day which starts off with all four race walks on the Mall, including the inaugural women's 50km event.", "time": "22:16:00"}

{"eng": "Sport of athletics"}, "score": 2, "type": "wiki", "id": "1053871"}], "url": "http://www.sify.com/news/sad-endings-for-bolt-farah-at-world-athletics-championships-roundup-news-others-rinqtSgggefci.html", "body": "London, Aug 13 (IANS) The World Athletics Championships just can't stop popping up surprises even as Jamaican great Usain Bolt and local hero Mohamed Farah bid farewell to their respective careers amid tears and defeat.\n\nIn the last race of his career, Bolt limped off the track while hosts Britain took the stunning 4x100m victory to the ecstacy of the capacity London Stadium spectators here on Saturday evening, reports Xinhua news agency.\n\nBolt, running the anchor leg, staggered halfway down the straight, dropping the baton before falling facing down. Dreaming of hanging up his running spikes without a defeat in a major championship, the 11-time world champion and eight-time Olympic titlist limped across the finish line.\n\nBolt had only taken a few strides when he appeared to suffer an injury to his left leg and fell to the track in pain. He stayed down for a couple of minutes before standing up and walking to the finish line.\n\nBritain won the gold in 37.47 seconds, the US took silver in 37.52 and Japan was third in 38.04. China, the silver medalist two years ago, finished fourth in 38.34 with second-leg runner Xie Zhenye just coming back from injury.\n\nThe British team of Chijindu Ujah, Adam Gemili, Danny Talbot and Nethaneel Mitchell-Blake broke the European record that had stood since 1999 by 0.26 seconds. That record was established by the British team of Jason Gardener, Darren Campbell, Marlon Devonish and Dwain Chambers as silver medal winners behind the USA at the 1999 IAAF World Championships in Seville, Spain.\n\nBritish anchor runner Nethaneel Michell-Blake dropped to the ground in blissful disbelief as his team beat the American squad consisting of newly crowned 100m world champion Justin Gatlin and runner-up Christian Coleman.\n\nIt brought back memories of the Athens Olympics in 2004, when Mark Lewis-Francis held off Maurice Greene to claim an unlikely Olympic victory over the Americans. The only other global senior championship success for Britain in the men's 4x100m relay was at the 1912 Olympics in Stockholm.\n\nIt was a rollercoaster night for the celebrating home fans when a couple of hours ago their emotion could only be described as disappointed when Farah failed in his quest for a fourth 5,000m world title in his farewell race just like Bolt.\n\nYoung Ethiopian star Muktar Edris has beaten the all-dominating Mohamed Farah of Britain to win the men's 5,000 metre title at the IAAF World Championships here.\n\nEdris, who was crowned world youth champion in 2012, produced a strong charge on the final stretch to register a time of 13 minutes and 32.79 seconds on Saturday evening, Xinhua news agency reported.\n\nThe 23-year-old, who won the first major senior world title of his career, stopped Farah from taking his fourth 5,000m world title.\n\nThe Somali-origin Farah has won Olympic gold in the men's 5,000m twice and has won the men's 10,000m title at this event.\n\nHowever on Saturday night, Farah had to be content with the second place after finishing with a time of 13:33.22. Paul Kipkemoi Chelimo of the US took bronze in 13:33.30. Farah, who was surrounded by Ethiopean runners going into the final stages of the race, produced a desperate final sprint but failed to catch up with the leader.\n\n\"I gave it everything,\" said Farah who initially curled up on the track in defeat and then was pulled up by Edris.\n\nJust like Jamaican great Usain Bolt, Farah finished his career with an unusual feeling of defeat.\n\nThe 34-year-old had won this event in the past three world championships and two Olympic Games, together with three world titles and two Olympic gold medals in 10,000m.\n\nHowever, he remains hero of the country, bagging one gold and one silver in London, which are the only medals the hosts have won by far.\n\nFarah, who had said this would be his last World Championships, will now turn his focus to marathon running.\n\nWhile Farah handed over his long distance crown, the next generation of Ethiopian runners announced their arrival on the world stage.\n\nEdris' fellow Ethiopians 2016 world indoor champion Yomif Kejelcha, 21, and this year's U-18 3,000m winner Selemon Barega were placed fourth and fifth respectively, indicating that the east Africans will continue to be a force to reckon at the international level.\n\nA surprise also took place in the field events as Johannes Vetter of Germany grabbed his first ever medal at a major global competition -- a golden one -- with his first attempt of 89.89 meters to win the men's javelin event even as defending champion Julius Yego and Olympic champion Thomas Rohler failed to deliver.\n\nJakub Vadlejch of Czech Republic finished second in 89.73m ahead of compatriot Petr Frydrych who registered 88.32m.\n\nRohler, from Germany, made a 88.26m throw in his second attempt and finished fourth while defending champion Julius Yego of Kenya was eliminated after the first three rounds.\n\nIn other events, Russia's Maria Lasitskene retained the women's high jump title.\n\nThe 24-year-old, competing as an authorized neutral athlete, cleared 2.03 meters for the gold medal. Ukraine's Yuliia Levchenko took silver in 2.01 and Poland's Kamila Licwinko was third in 1.99.\n\nLasitskene, who missed last year's Rio Olympics because of Russia's suspension, failed at 1.99 twice but regained form thereafter.\n\n\"My two failed attempts at 1.99m woke me up,\" she said.\n\n\"A gold medal here was my main goal for this season but certainly I would like to raise the bar a bit higher. I didn't like any one of my attempts at 2.08m.\"\n\nShe challenged 2.08 three times but failed.\n\n\"It was an unbelievable championships for me. I was focussed from the opening jump until the last attempt. I didn't allow myself to get emotional,\" Levchenko said.\n\n\"At 2.01m it was not my best technical attempt. I thought that such a height would not forgive the mistakes I made.\"\n\nMeanwhile, USA regained the women's 4x100m world crown which they last won at the 2011 World Championships in Daegu as they sailed to victory in 41.82 seconds while hosts Britain gladly bagged a silver in 42.12. Defending champions Jamaica clocked 42.19 for the bronze.\n\nAustralia's Sally Pearson won her second world women's 100 meters hurdles title in six years.\n\nPearson, 30, who won the world title in 2011 and Olympic gold five years ago, clocked 12.59 seconds for the gold. American Dawn Harper Nelson, who won the Olympic gold in Beijing and silver in London behind Pearson, took silver in 12.63 seconds. Germany's Pamela Dutkiewicz finished third in 12.72 seconds.\n\n\"It's been a long journey back from injury but to get this moment and go and celebrate in front of my family is unreal. This is just so incredible to be a world champion again,\" Pearson, also the silver medallist in the Beijing Olympics, said.\n\n\"I love this stadium. I love the people and I'm so happy to have been back here doing the same thing again (winning gold). It's a relief to be world champion.\"\n\nRio Olympic silver medalist Kevin Mayer claimed France's second gold from the men's decathlon with a total of 8,768 points. Germany's Rico Freimuth, bronze winner two years ago in the Beijing worlds, took silver in 8,564 points and his compatriot Kai Kazmirek got the bronze in 8,488.\n\n--IANS\n\najb/\n\nSEARCH", "time": "10:56:00"}

despite his glorious track career ending with defeat in the 5,000 metres world championships final.\n\nAlthough his silver medal performance was pushed out of the limelight by the drama of the men's 4x100m relay, which saw fellow legend Usain Bolt collapse with cramp on his own swansong as Britain pulled off a remarkable victory, as well as the thrilling opening of the Premier League season, Farah still commanded many column inches.\n\nThe 34-year-old saw his global championship win streak of 10 gold medals dating back to the 5,000m at the 2011 world championships ended as Muktar Edris of Ethiopia held off his desperate charge in the finishing straight.\n\n\"End of the track for Mo\" headlined The Sunday Times, adding that it was a \"shattering defeat in front of an adoring crowd\".\n\nHowever, the paper eulogised about the performance by Farah - who came to Britain with his mother and two of his brothers from Somalia via a spell with his grandparents in Djibouti aged just eight - in the stadium where he had memorably achieved his first Olympic double in 2012.\n\n\"If defeat is the making of a true champion, then Mo Farah left the track at the Olympic stadium last night as the greatest champion of all,\" wrote its sports writer.\n\n\"That he failed, beaten finally, for the first time at a major championships since 2011, by Muktar Edris of Ethiopia, stripped nothing from the legend.\"\n\nThe Sun on Sunday, never one to miss out on an eye-catching pun, perhaps unkindly went with \"Slow Mo\".\n\nHowever, Farah -- who has had a tense relationship with large sections of the British media over the questions raised by his loyalty to controversial United States-based coach Alberto Salazar -- would have been happier with what followed.\n\n\"The 34-year-old is hanging up his spikes to take to the roads in the marathon after a stellar career which has seen him establish himself as one of the all-time greats of the sport,\" purred the Sun correspondent.\n\n\"Yet despite the huge support from the home crowd packed into the London Stadium, Britain's hero was finally knocked off his perch as the king of long-distance running.\"\n\nThe their race.\n\n\"It is what it is, I just meant that I was going to take Mo down,\" said Chelimo.\n\nThe Observer remarked that those who had come in their thousands with their faces painted with \"Go Saturday.\n\n\"He curled into the foetal position at the finish, beaten in a major final for the first time in six years,\" wrote the correspondent.\n\n\"Silver on this occasion stung like defeat and "815059"}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jason_Gardener", "label": {"eng": "Jason Gardener"}, "score": 3, "type": "person", "id": "827648"}], "url": "http://www.sify.com/news/sad-endings-for-bolt-farah-at-world-athletics-meet-intro-roundup-news-others-rinrDVggajfbh.html", "body": "London, Aug 13 (IANS) The World Athletics Championships just can't stop popping up surprises even as Jamaican great Usain Bolt and local hero Mohamed Farah bid farewell to their respective careers amid tears and defeat.\n\nIn the last race of his career, Bolt limped off the track while hosts Britain took the stunning 4x100m victory to the ecstasy of the capacity London Stadium spectators here on Saturday evening, reports Xinhua news agency.\n\nBolt had only taken a few strides when he appeared to suffer an injury to his left leg around 30 metres into the anchor leg. He dropped the baton before falling face down to the track in pain.\n\nThe 11-time world champion and eight-time Olympic titlist stayed down for a couple of minutes and refused the offer of a wheelchair from medics before standing up and walking to the finish line.\n\nFor all his stellar achievements, it book-ended a professional life in the fast lane that started in similar fashion, when he limped across the line last in the 200m final on his World Championships debut as an injury-prone 18-year-old in Helsinki back in 2005.\n\n\"Everybody was jelly. Everybody was pumped. It just happened (Usain's injury). Usain Bolt's name will always live on,\" Jamaica's first leg runner Omar McLeod said.\n\nBolt had anchored Jamaica to victory in each of the previous six global championship 4x100m finals, stretching back to the 2009 World Championships with an average winning margin of 0.49.\n\nThis time, with 110m hurdles champion Omar McLeod on the lead off leg, Julian Forte on leg two and 2011 world 100m champion Blake on three, they were far from the polished model that scorched to the 2012 Olympic title in a world record time of 36.84 seconds.\n\nBritain won the gold in 37.47 seconds, the US took silver in 37.52 and Japan was third in 38.04. China, the silver medallist two years ago, finished fourth in 38.34 with second-leg runner Xie Zhenye just coming back from injury.\n\nThe British team of Chijindu Ujah, Adam Gemili, Danny Talbot and Nethaneel Mitchell-Blake broke the European record -- that had stood since 1999 -- by 0.26 seconds. That record was established by the British team of Jason Gardener, Darren Campbell, Marlon Devonish and Dwain Chambers as silver medal winners behind the USA at the 1999 IAAF World Championships in Seville, Spain.\n\nBritish anchor runner Michell-Blake dropped to the ground in blissful disbelief as his team beat the American squad consisting of newly crowned 100m world champion Justin Gatlin and runner-up Christian Coleman.\n\nIt brought back memories of the Athens Olympics in 2004, when Mark Lewis-Francis held off Maurice Greene to claim an unlikely Olympic victory over the Americans. The only other global senior championship success for Britain in the men's 4x100m relay was at the 1912 Olympics in Stockholm.\n\nIt was a roller-coaster night for the celebrating home fans when a couple of hours ago their emotion could only be described as disappointed when Farah failed in his quest for a fourth 5,000m world title in his farewell race just like Bolt.\n\nYoung Ethiopian star Muktar Edris has beaten the all-dominating Mohamed Farah of Britain to win the men's 5,000 metre title at the IAAF World Championships here.\n\nEdris, who was crowned world youth champion in 2012, produced a strong charge on the final stretch to register a time of 13 minutes and 32.79 seconds on Saturday evening, Xinhua news agency reported.\n\nThe 23-year-old, who won the first major senior world title of his career, stopped Farah from taking his fourth 5,000m world title.\n\nThe Somali-origin Farah has won Olympic gold in the men's 5,000m twice and has won the men's 10,000m title at this event.\n\nHowever, on Saturday night, Farah had to be content with the second place after finishing with a time of 13:33.22. Paul Kipkemoi Chelimo of the US took bronze in 13:33.30. Farah, who was surrounded by Ethiopian runners going into the final stages of the race, produced a desperate final sprint but failed to catch up with the leader.\n\n\"I gave it everything,\" said Farah who initially curled up on the track in defeat and then was pulled up by Edris.\n\n\"It takes so much out of me. Tactically I was trying to cover every move. They had the game plan; one of them was going to sacrifice themselves... and the better man won on the day,\" he added.\n\nJust like Bolt, Farah finished his career with an unusual feeling of defeat.\n\nThe 34-year-old had won this event in the past three world championships and two Olympic Games, together with three world titles and two Olympic gold medals in 10,000m.\n\nHowever, he remains hero of the country, bagging one gold and one silver in London, which are the only medals the hosts have won by far.\n\nFarah, who had said this would be his last World Championships, will now turn his focus to marathon running.\n\nWhile Farah handed over his long distance crown, the next generation of Ethiopian runners announced their arrival on the world stage.\n\nEdris' fellow Ethiopians 2016 world indoor champion Yomif Kejelcha, 21, and this year's U-18 3,000m winner Selemon Barega were placed fourth and fifth respectively, indicating that the east Africans will continue to be a force to reckon at the international level.\n\nA surprise also took place in the field events as Johannes Vetter of Germany grabbed his first ever medal at a major global competition -- a golden one -- with his first attempt of 89.89 meters to win the men's javelin event even as defending champion Julius Yego and Olympic champion Thomas Rohler failed to deliver.\n\nJakub Vadlejch of Czech Republic finished second in 89.73m ahead of compatriot Petr Frydrych who registered 88.32m.\n\nRohler, from Germany, made a 88.26m throw in his second attempt and finished fourth while defending champion Julius Yego of Kenya was eliminated after the first three rounds.\n\nIn other events, Russia's Maria Lasitskene retained the women's high jump title.\n\nThe 24-year-old, competing as an authorized neutral athlete, cleared 2.03 meters for the gold medal. Ukraine's Yuliia Levchenko took silver in 2.01 and Poland's Kamila Licwinko was third in 1.99.\n\nLasitskene, who missed last year's Rio Olympics because of Russia's suspension, failed at 1.99 twice but regained form thereafter.\n\n\"My two failed attempts at 1.99m woke me up,\" she said.\n\n\"A gold medal here was my main goal for this season but certainly I would like to raise the bar a bit higher. I didn't like any one of my attempts at 2.08m.\"\n\nShe challenged 2.08 three times but failed.\n\n\"It was an unbelievable championships for me. I was focussed from the opening jump until the last attempt. I didn't allow myself to get emotional,\" Levchenko said.\n\n\"At 2.01m it was not my best technical attempt. I thought that such a height would not forgive the mistakes I made.\"\n\nMeanwhile, USA regained the women's 4x100m world crown which they last won at the 2011 World Championships in Daegu as they sailed to victory in 41.82 seconds while hosts Britain gladly bagged a silver in 42.12. Defending champions Jamaica clocked 42.19 for the bronze.\n\nAustralia's Sally Pearson won her second world women's 100 meters hurdles title in six years.\n\nPearson, 30, who won the world title in 2011 and Olympic gold five years ago, clocked 12.59 seconds for the gold. American Dawn Harper Nelson, who won the Olympic gold in Beijing and silver in London behind Pearson, took silver in 12.63 seconds. Germany's Pamela Dutkiewicz finished third in 12.72 seconds.\n\n\"It's been a long journey back from injury but to get this moment and go and celebrate in front of my family is unreal. This is just so incredible to be a world champion again,\" Pearson, also the silver medallist in the Beijing Olympics, said.\n\n\"I love this stadium. I love the people and I'm so happy to have been back here doing the same thing again (winning gold). It's a relief to be world champion.\"\n\nRio Olympic silver medallist Kevin Mayer claimed France's second gold from the men's decathlon with a total of 8,768 points. Germany's Rico Freimuth, bronze winner two years ago in the Beijing worlds, took silver in 8,564 points and his compatriot Kai Kazmirek got the bronze in 8,488.\n\n--IANS\n\najb/dg\n\nSEARCH", "time": "12:20:00"}

silver medal performance was pushed out of the limelight by the drama of the men's 4x100m relay, which saw fellow legend Usain Bolt collapse with cramp on his own swansong as Britain pulled off a remarkable victory, as well as the thrilling opening of the Premier League season, Farah still commanded many column inches.\n\nThe 34-year-old saw his global championship win streak of 10 gold medals dating back to the 5,000m at the 2011 world championships ended as Muktar Edris of Ethiopia held off his desperate charge in the finishing straight.\n\n\"End of the track for Mo\" headlined The Sunday Times, adding that it was a \"shattering defeat in front of an adoring crowd\".\n\nHowever, the paper eulogised about the performance by Farah -- who came to Britain with his mother and two of his brothers from Somalia via a spell with his grandparents in Djibouti aged just eight -- in the stadium where he had memorably achieved his first Olympic double in 2012.\n\n\"If defeat is the making of a true champion, then Mo Farah left the track at the Olympic stadium last night as the greatest champion of all,\" wrote its sports writer.\n\n\"That he failed, beaten finally, for the first time at a major championships since 2011, by Muktar Edris of Ethiopia, stripped nothing from the legend.\"\n\nThe Sun on Sunday, never one to miss out on an eye-catching pun, perhaps unkindly went with \"Slow Mo\".\n\nHowever, Farah -- who has had a tense relationship with large sections of the British media over the questions raised by his loyalty to controversial United States-based coach Alberto Salazar -- would have been happier with what followed.\n\n\"The 34-year-old is hanging up his spikes to take to the roads in the marathon after a stellar career which has seen him establish himself as one of the all-time greats of the sport,\" purred the Sun correspondent.\n\n\"Yet despite the huge support from the home crowd packed into the London Stadium, Britain's hero was finally knocked off his perch Britain's most successful ever athlete.\n\nAnd they took aim at America's Kenyan-born bronze medallist Paul Chelimo for making Farah's trademark 'Mobot' gesture and then running his hand across his throat as the 5,000m runners lined up before their race.\n\n\"It is what it is, I just meant that I was going to take Mo down,\" said Chelimo.\n\nThe Observer remarked that those who had come in their thousands with their faces painted with \"Go Mo!\" and banners with \"Run Farah Run\" were to be left disappointed.\n\nIt also commented on how his soon to turn five twin daughters Aisha and Amani had "Dwain Chambers"}, "score": 3, "type": "person", "id": "723555"}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marlon_Devonish", "label": {"eng": "Marlon Devonish"}, "score": 3, "type": "person", "id": "815059"}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jason_Gardener", "label": {"eng": "Jason Gardener"}, "score": 3, "type": "person", "id": "827648"}], "url": "http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/sad-endings-for-bolt-farah-at-world-athletics-meet-intro-roundup-117081300443_1.html", "body": "The World Athletics Championships just can't stop popping up surprises even as Jamaican great Usain Bolt and local hero Mohamed Farah bid farewell to their respective careers amid tears and defeat.\n\nIn the last race of his career, Bolt limped off the track while hosts Britain took the stunning 4x100m victory to the ecstasy of the capacity London Stadium spectators here on Saturday evening, reports Xinhua news agency.\n\nBolt had only taken a few strides when he appeared to suffer an injury to his left leg around 30 metres into the anchor leg. He dropped the baton before falling face down to the track in pain.\n\nThe 11-time world champion and eight-time Olympic titlist stayed down for a couple of minutes and refused the offer of a wheelchair from medics before standing up and walking to the finish line.\n\nFor all his stellar achievements, it book-ended a professional life in the fast lane that started in similar fashion, when he limped across the line last in the 200m final on his World Championships debut as an injury-prone 18-year-old in Helsinki back in 2005.\n\n\"Everybody was jelly. Everybody was pumped. It just happened (Usain's injury). Usain Bolt's name will always live on,\" Jamaica's first leg runner Omar McLeod said.\n\nBolt had anchored Jamaica to victory in each of the previous six global championship 4x100m finals, stretching back to the 2009 World Championships with an average winning margin of 0.49.\n\nThis time, with 110m hurdles champion Omar McLeod on the lead off leg, Julian Forte on leg two and 2011 world 100m champion Blake on three, they were far from the polished model that scorched to the 2012 Olympic title in a world record time of 36.84 seconds.\n\nBritain won the gold in 37.47 seconds, the US took silver in 37.52 and Japan was third in 38.04. China, the silver medallist two years ago, finished fourth in 38.34 with second-leg runner Xie Zhenye just coming back from injury.\n\nThe British team of Chijindu Ujah, Adam Gemili, Danny Talbot and Nethaneel Mitchell-Blake broke the European record -- that had stood since 1999 -- by 0.26 seconds. That record was established by the British team of Jason Gardener, Darren Campbell, Marlon Devonish and Dwain Chambers as silver medal winners behind the USA at the 1999 IAAF World Championships in Seville, Spain.\n\nBritish anchor runner Michell-Blake dropped to the ground in blissful disbelief as his team beat the American squad consisting of newly crowned 100m world champion Justin Gatlin and runner-up Christian Coleman.\n\nIt brought back memories of the Athens Olympics in 2004, when Mark Lewis-Francis held off Maurice Greene to claim an unlikely Olympic victory over the Americans. The only other global senior championship success for Britain in the men's 4x100m relay was at the 1912 Olympics in Stockholm.\n\nIt was a roller-coaster night for the celebrating home fans when a couple of hours ago their emotion could only be described as disappointed when Farah failed in his quest for a fourth 5,000m world title in his farewell race just like Bolt.\n\nYoung Ethiopian star Muktar Edris has beaten the all-dominating Mohamed Farah of Britain to win the men's 5,000 metre title at the IAAF World Championships here.\n\nEdris, who was crowned world youth champion in 2012, produced a strong charge on the final stretch to register a time of 13 minutes and 32.79 seconds on Saturday evening, Xinhua news agency reported.\n\nThe 23-year-old, who won the first major senior world title of his career, stopped Farah from taking his fourth 5,000m world title.\n\nThe Somali-origin Farah has won Olympic gold in the men's 5,000m twice and has won the men's 10,000m title at this event.\n\nHowever, on Saturday night, Farah had to be content with the second place after finishing with a time of 13:33.22. Paul Kipkemoi Chelimo of the US took bronze in 13:33.30. Farah, who was surrounded by Ethiopian runners going into the final stages of the race, produced a desperate final sprint but failed to catch up with the leader.\n\n\"I gave it everything,\" said Farah who initially curled up on the track in defeat and then was pulled up by Edris.\n\n\"It takes so much out of me. Tactically I was trying to cover every move. They had the game plan; one of them was going to sacrifice themselves... and the better man won on the day,\" he added.\n\nJust like Bolt, Farah finished his career with an unusual feeling of defeat.\n\nThe 34-year-old had won this event in the past three world championships and two Olympic Games, together with three world titles and two Olympic gold medals in 10,000m.\n\nHowever, he remains hero of the country, bagging one gold and one silver in London, which are the only medals the hosts have won by far.\n\nFarah, who had said this would be his last World Championships, will now turn his focus to marathon running.\n\nWhile Farah handed over his long distance crown, the next generation of Ethiopian runners announced their arrival on the world stage.\n\nEdris' fellow Ethiopians 2016 world indoor champion Yomif Kejelcha, 21, and this year's U-18 3,000m winner Selemon Barega were placed fourth and fifth respectively, indicating that the east Africans will continue to be a force to reckon at the international level.\n\nA surprise also took place in the field events as Johannes Vetter of Germany grabbed his first ever medal at a major global competition -- a golden one -- with his first attempt of 89.89 meters to win the men's javelin event even as defending champion Julius Yego and Olympic champion Thomas Rohler failed to deliver.\n\nJakub Vadlejch of Czech Republic finished second in 89.73m ahead of compatriot Petr Frydrych who registered 88.32m.\n\nRohler, from Germany, made a 88.26m throw in his second attempt and finished fourth while defending champion Julius Yego of Kenya was eliminated after the first three rounds.\n\nIn other events, Russia's Maria Lasitskene retained the women's high jump title.\n\nThe 24-year-old, competing as an authorized neutral athlete, cleared 2.03 meters for the gold medal. Ukraine's Yuliia Levchenko took silver in 2.01 and Poland's Kamila Licwinko was third in 1.99.\n\nLasitskene, who missed last year's Rio Olympics because of Russia's suspension, failed at 1.99 twice but regained form thereafter.\n\n\"My two failed attempts at 1.99m woke me up,\" she said.\n\n\"A gold medal here was my main goal for this season but certainly I would like to raise the bar a bit higher. I didn't like any one of my attempts at 2.08m.\"\n\nShe challenged 2.08 three times but failed.\n\n\"It was an unbelievable championships for me. I was focussed from the opening jump until the last attempt. I didn't allow myself to get emotional,\" Levchenko said.\n\n\"At 2.01m it was not my best technical attempt. I thought that such a height would not forgive the mistakes I made.\"\n\nMeanwhile, USA regained the women's 4x100m world crown which they last won at the 2011 World Championships in Daegu as they sailed to victory in 41.82 seconds while hosts Britain gladly bagged a silver in 42.12. Defending champions Jamaica clocked 42.19 for the bronze.\n\nAustralia's Sally Pearson won her second world women's 100 meters hurdles title in six years.\n\nPearson, 30, who won the world title in 2011 and Olympic gold five years ago, clocked 12.59 seconds for the gold. American Dawn Harper Nelson, who won the Olympic gold in Beijing and silver in London behind Pearson, took silver in 12.63 seconds. Germany's Pamela Dutkiewicz finished third in 12.72 seconds.\n\n\"It's been a long journey back from injury but to get this moment and go and celebrate in front of my family is unreal. This is just so incredible to be a world champion again,\" Pearson, also the silver medallist in the Beijing Olympics, said.\n\n\"I love this stadium. "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alberto_Salazar", "label": {"eng": "Alberto Salazar"}, "score": 3, "type": "person", "id": "366378"}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joanne_Pavey", "label": "442418"}, {"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muktar_Edris", "label": {"eng": "Muktar Edris"}, "score": 3, "type": "person", "id": "709359"}], "url": "http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/aug/13/mo-farah-10000m-final-edris", "body": "The tank has almost run dry. Mo Farah ended his last major track race with a silver medal in the 5,000m after a desperate lunge in the final few strides propelled him from fourth place to second, coming up just short in his quest for a career-capping win at the World Championships in London last night.\n\nThe 34-year-old, legs pumping as he tried to catch the leader, agony etched across his face, was beaten at a major championships for the first time in six years by Muktar Edris of Ethiopia.\n\nFarah collapsed in disappointment, before picking himself up to jog around the track, composing himself and, occasionally, smiling for selfies and autographs with the thousands of fans in the stadium who had chanted his name and urged him on. Yet he was clearly disappointed not to end on a high.\n\n\"I thought I could get inside at the end, but my legs had had it,\" he said, admitting that the 10,000m win last weekend on 4 August had taken even more out of him than in championships gone by. \"London is my home and it has been fantastic to be here again. The last week or so has been incredible. I've really enjoyed the journey.\"\n\nUsain Bolt's journey also ended on Saturday, albeit in even more agonising fashion as he pulled up on the anchor leg of the men's 4x100m relay. The crowd had little time to take it in as Great Britain's CJ Ujah, Adam Gemili, Danny Talbot and Nethaneel Mitchell-Blake ran a near-perfect race to hold off the fancied US team and take gold in the race, with Japan taking bronze as Bolt collapsed halfway down the home straight.\n\nFarah's final appearance in the London Stadium at a major competition seals one of the most successful careers any British athlete has ever had. Farah has won four Olympic gold medals in the 5,000m and 10,000m in London and Rio, as well as almost every major championship race at those distances since 2010. He has several other awards and was knighted earlier this year. Sir Mo is a heavyweight British icon, all nine stone of him.\n\nHis achievements are underlined by the hardship of his early life. Farah fled Mogadishu as an eight-year-old when civil war hit the Somali capital, coming to live in London with his father, Mukhtar, who was born in the UK.\n\nYet even when he finally hangs up his running spikes -- Farah has two more appearances to make, at Diamond League races in Birmingham and Zurich -- he will face one last challenge: to prove in the court of public opinion that he has never been a drugs cheat. There is no case for the prosecution against Farah himself. The taint comes from association with his coach, Alberto Salazar. The Cuban-born American has been under investigation by the United States anti-doping agency (Usada) for two years since a documentary by BBC's Panorama and ProPublica carried allegations that he had experimented with doping and gave athletes unneeded prescription medicines.\n\nFarah has beaten down questions for so long that he is, unsurprisingly, sick of answering them. He cannot prove his innocence, although even critical voices like Olympic bronze medal-winning heptathlete Kelly Sotherton -- who believes Farah can't be considered a \"legend\" due to his lack of records -- say he has \"full integrity\" and is honest.\n\nPart of the suspicion has come because he flourished relatively late in his career -- although not as late as some middle- and long-distance runners such as Jo Pavey, who became 10,000m European champion at the age of 40, after giving birth to her second child.\n\nFarah's talent was spotted early enough. His PE teacher in west London, Alan Watkinson, guided him away from a possible footballing career on to the running track. The first test was a cross-country championship. \"He literally didn't know what was going on and ran in the wrong direction,\" Watkinson said in 2010. \"He had to follow the other kids around and he still managed to finish second.\"\n\nFarah's promise became major success in 2001, when he won the 5,000m at the European junior athletics championships in Athens at the age of 18. Afterwards, he struggled for but won few honours and in 2008 failed to qualify for the 5,000m final at the Beijing Olympics.\n\nHis resurgence coincided with the build-up to the London Olympics, when British athletes were showered with money to ensure a bumper crop of medals in 2012. He began training with Kenya's best runners, living with them, joining them at high-altitude training camps in Ethiopia and Kenya, and focusing harder on his career. Farah was picked as a winner, and he began to deliver. In 2010, he collected golds at the European championships in his two favourite distances, then set a 5,000m national record. A year later, he became world champion over 5,000m -- the first British man to win the title. The stage was set for the London Games.\n\nMeanwhile his personal life had also settled. In 2010 he married Tania Nell, whom he met as a student, and moved the following year to the US to work with Salazar on his Nike Oregon Project. Their twin daughters were born in the year of the London Games and Farah was one of Britain's heroes, winning gold at the London Stadium in the 5,000m and 10,000m. He didn't stop there. He has won every major championship race since -- 13 in a row, including his dramatic 10,000m win last week.\n\n\"To have achieved what I have achieved has been incredible. I don't think there's enough words to explain the journey,\" he said. \"Yeah, it is emotional but it has been a long career. You guys have seen me since I was a child, running around, going to the English schools. To come this far has been incredible.\"\n\nMO'S MEDAL TRIUMPHS\n\nOlympic Games: Four gold medals - dedicated to his children - in the 5,000m and 10,000m at London 2012 and Rio 2016.\n\nWorld championships: Double gold medals in Moscow 2013 and Beijing 2015. off his career with anything but glory.\n\nHe produced another thrilling and brave run knowing he was the man everyone else in the field wanted to beat but just ran out of steam in the dash for home.\n\nFarah said: \"I gave it my all, I don't think there was any more I could have. The better man won on the day.\"\n\nIn a highly tactical race, Farah had positioned himself just off the pace throughout as he attempted to avoid the jostling that made him work so hard in the 10,000m.\n\nBut just as the bell sounded, three Ethiopians all burst forward at the same time, and for 150m Farah was swallowed up and unable to find his way out of the bunch.\n\nOld rival Paul Chelimo then made his move approaching the final bend as he and the British star desperately tried to haul in Muktar Edris and Yomif Kejelcha who had suddenly opened up a five metre gap at the front.\n\nRoared on by the home crowd Farah dug deep coming into the home straight, forcing his way past Chilemo and Kejelcha.\n\nBut try as he might he was unable to match the electric finish of Edris and the Ehtiopian took that title with Farah being forced to settle for second.\n\nFellow Brit Andrew Butchart came home eight as he just failed to match the blistering last lap pace.\n\nHe said: \"The race went as my coach said it would but I didn't react. They were too quick for me. I am happy with it. It was my first world champs final so I have to walk away pleased.\n\n\"I'm gutted for Mo, but he is the best in the world. Look at what he has done. He leaves a legend. I know he will be upset.\"", "time": "20:29:00"}

"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/athletics/2017/08/09/mo-farah-splashes-puddles-customary-poise-lay-platform-11thsuccessive/", "body": "If you had ever wondered what it might be like to watch athletics from inside a car wash, then this was your chance. A drenching evening at the Olympic Park, with Stratford wreathed in Stygian gloom and rain provided by the special effects team on 'The Day After Tomorrow', seemed a fitting setting for more British medal prospects to take a bath. All of them, that is, besides Sir Mo Farah, who sploshed through the puddles with his customary poise to lay the platform for an 11th successive global title.\n\nIt defied belief that this was Farah's penultimate appearance at global championships. He looked curiously ageless as he swept through his 5,000 metres heat on Wednesday night, controlling the rhythm of the race, and yet he was on the cusp of bidding this, his beloved stadium, goodbye. The worry is that he is taking the last vestige of British hope at this level with him.\n\nFarah had kindled the home fires with a wonderful statement on the first evening, with his 10,000 metres triumph, but from there a catalogue of British near-misses has reduced those flames to a flicker. With Dame Jessica Ennis-Hill happily retired and pregnant with her second child, and Greg Rutherford injured but most likely with his peak well behind him, Farah is the last member of Super Saturday's golden trinity left standing. On this wettest of Wednesdays, it felt necessary to appreciate his remorseless consistency while we still could.\n\nMo Farah on one of his 'toughest' races after world 10,000m gold 00:58\n\nIn an unfamiliar sight, Farah crossed the line second, behind Ethiopia's Yomif Kejelcha, but he seldom looked troubled. Despite having made a shivering gesture at American Eric Jenkins as he took to the track, the experience of running in the damp chill of an East London evening was second nature. He used to race for Newham & Essex Beagles Athletic Club, after all, so the proposition of 12\u00bd laps here at the borough's gleaming citadel was hardly a hardship.\n\nThere are myriad explanations for British athletes' under-performance at these championships, from an unstructured talent identification system to a lack of competitive exposure, but it paid to listen to Farah for a guide to reaching the summit and staying there. \"I'm a bit tired, but you have just got to recover,\" he said. \"I'm happy to qualify - it's always difficult, coming so soon after the 10,000. Rounds are the hardest part. I had to switch on and go again. But anything is possible. Train hard and win easy, that's what the Kenyans say. I've been given a chance in life. For all the young kids out there, you should believe that you can do it as well.\"\n\nMoment Mo Farah wins 10,000m at IAAF World Championships 00:40\n\nFarah had scuffs and bruises from an attritional 10,000m, in which he was clattered twice by his rivals, but he explained that a night back home with his family in Teddington, where he spent his teenage years, had helped him rejuvenate. This return to the 5,000 marked a study in composure and restraint. The slow pace of the early laps threatened to unsettle him, but he stayed on the fringes of the pack to avoid the potential havoc of passing lapped runners in a bunched field. Mentally, as he is not shy of admitting, he remains tougher than the rest.\n\nHis only disappointment, perhaps, lay in the fate of his training partner, Bashar Abdi. Farah had repeatedly been looking over his shoulder for the Belgian, trying to leave him space, but Abdi was ultimately run out of a qualifying spot by Canada's Justyn Knight. He will be joined in the final by Andy Butchart of Scotland, who came through the second, feisty heat. \"I'm going for a medal - not another fourth place, like the rest of our guys,\" he said, with a mischievous smirk.\n\nThe prize that awaits Farah on Saturday night is a glittering one. Where Usain Bolt fell short of scripting the perfect ending, with his bronze medal behind Justin Gatlin, Farah clutches a chance to retire from the track with a six-year winning streak on this stage intact. Not since the 10,000m in Daegu, in 2011, when he was scuppered by a 52-second last lap from Ibrahim Jeilan, has he been vanquished in his period of working with Alberto Salazar. It is an astounding sequence, and it is not one he trusts will end this weekend, as he closes in on a 'quintuple-double' of distance titles.\n\n\"It isn't easy,\" he said. \"You have seen that with Usain Bolt. It would have been great to see him win, but it doesn't always happen that way. No one is going to give it to you, no matter who you are. It would be pretty amazing to bow out with another double gold, but these guys are coming for me. I have to be ready.\" The familiar sense of conviction was rising back to the surface. \"I am going to do it,\" he assured, breaking into a smile.", "time": "21:47:00"}
