"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/aug/13/mo-farah-media-world-athletics-championships", "body": "* Farah second after painful end to 5,000m at World Championships\n\n* Briton accuses press of trying to 'destroy' his legacy in athletics\n\nMo Farah has accused sections of the media of trying to \"destroy\" his achievements on the track with unfounded allegations against his legendary coach Alberto Salazar and insinuations about how he attained his success.\n\nSpeaking the morning after his glittering championship track career came to an end with a painful 5,000m defeat in the London Stadium, Britain's most successful ever athlete insisted his 10 world and Olympic titles had come about purely through hard work.\n\n\"History doesn't lie,\" Farah told his critics. \"What I achieved over the years, people are proud of me. You can write what you like. The fact is I've achieved what I have from hard work and dedication. Putting my balls on the line, year after year and delivering for my country.\"\n\nAs the exchanges grew more heated, Farah asked why some journalists kept bringing up his relationship with Salazar, who helped turn him from a very good athlete into a great one after he joined the coach's Nike Oregon Project training group in late 2010. Salazar has been under investigation by the United States Anti-Doping Agency for the past two years but has always vehemently denied any wrongdoing.\n\n\"It's like a broken record, repeating myself,\" said Farah, who gave everything during a thrilling last lap only to finish second to the Ethiopian Muktar Edris on Saturday night. \"If I've crossed the line, if Alberto's crossed the line, why bring it up year after year, making it into headlines? I've achieved what I have achieved - you're trying to destroy it.\"\n\nAs Farah pointed out, while Salazar has been his coach on paper - which includes writing his workouts - the day-to-day training has been facilitated by the British team. \"How many races has he been to this year for me or last year?\" Farah asked. \"He hasn't been to any.\n\n\"I've been pretty much by myself with the guidance of Alberto, as you all know. I was capable of doing the job. It didn't make any difference to me. I know what I wanted to do. I was in a training camp for the British team.\"\n\nFarah also suggested that parts of the media, which has questioned the nature of his relationship with the controversial coach Jama Aden and then reported on the leak of his athlete's biological passport by the Russian hackers Fancy Bears, had an agenda against him.\n\n\"There's nothing else to be said,\" he said. \"Sometimes I find it bizarre how certain people write certain things to suit how they want to sell the story. You guys get to me - you never write the facts. The fact is, over the years, I have achieved a lot through hard work and pain.\"\n\n\"So many times, you guys have been unfair to me,\" he added. \"I know that. But say it how it is. I want you to write the truth about what's out there and educate people out there. But be honest with them. If you say Mo Farah has done something wrong' prove it.\"\n\nFarah refused to say whether he would be coached by Salazar next year when he tackles the formidable challenge of the marathon. But he admitted he was sad to leave the track after so many glittering successes.\n\n\"It has definitely hit me,\" he said. \"I got emotional on Saturday night. All good things in life must come to an end at some point. What goes up must come back down. I wanted to end on a high. But it happens. The better man won on the day. That's part of athletics. Fair credit to the other guys to be able to go. They had three guys in the team - they said 'one of you won't get a medal'. To beat Mo, it's taken them six years to do it but you've got to give it to them.\"\n\nHe also conceded that stepping up to 26.2 miles would not be easy. \"No one is going to give it to me. The roads are a whole new game. I've got to learn it and understand my weakness. It's going to take a while to understand the marathon.\" Farah also insisted that he was open to the idea of helping the next generation of British distance runners. \"It's important that we get into the sport and help others,\" he said. \"Christine Ohuruogu has been helping out with the relay and will continue to leave a legacy behind.\n\n\"It's about not thinking selfishly, not thinking financially. If we love the sport, you try to help others and I believe the knowledge and what I've learned over the years, I can contribute towards the younger kids and make a difference.\n\n\"You see Kyle Langford, Laura Muir, the relay boys - there are a lot of youngsters coming through,\" he added. \"I think we can make a difference.\"", "time": "13:03:00"}

I don't know why.\"\n\nFarah won silver in Saturday's 5,000 metres at the World Athletics Championships -- his final track race of a career in which he won two successive Olympic 10,000 and 5,000 gold medal doubles.\n\nThe 34-year-old, who was born in Somalia and moved to Britain at the age of eight, has also won three world titles each in the 5,000 metres and 10,000 metres.\n\nIn February, Farah's coach Alberto Salazar denied administering banned supplements to his athletes and issued a firm rebuttal of what he said were false allegations against him in a British newspaper.\n\nThe Sunday Times had reported that Salazar had used prohibited infusions of supplements to improve the performance of his runners, citing what the newspaper said was a leaked United States Anti-Doping Agency (USADA) report.\n\nFarah has repeatedly denied wrongdoing.\n\n\"It's like a broken record repeating myself,\" said Farah when the subject was brought up on Sunday. \"If I have crossed the line, and Mo Farah has done something wrong, then prove it.\"\n\n\"You can write what you like but I'm a clean athlete... and I sleep well at night, loving my kids, hugging my kids, showing (them) what's right. That's all that counts.\"\n\nFarah, speaking calmly but looking exasperated, said his achievements spoke for themselves.\n\n\"History doesn't lie -- everybody's proud of me,\" he said.\n\n\"The fact is, I work hard at what I do and I achieve (it) through hard work... putting my balls on the line, year after year, and delivering for my country, and for the people out there.\"\n\n\"I'm going to still keep fighting, keep working, making my country proud,\" said Farah, who will now concentrate on running marathons. \"I am proud to be British and put my GB vest on and do it for my country.\"\n\n(This article has not been edited by DNA's editorial team and is auto-generated from an agency feed.)", "time": "17:28:00"}

World Championships just can't stop producing surprises, which could hardly be pleasant memories for Jamaican great Usain Bolt and home hero Mohamed Farah who both bid farewell to their careers.\n\nIn his last race of his career, Bolt limped off the track while hosts Britain took a stunning 4x100m victory to the ecstacy of the capacity London Stadium spectators, a never better redemption for a disappointing silver in the men's 5,000m.\n\nBolt, running the anchor leg, staggered halfway down the straight, dropping the baton before falling face down. Dreaming of hanging up his running spikes as \"unbeatable\", the 11-time world champion and 8-time Olympic titlist limped across the finish line.\n\n\"Everybody was jelly. Everybody was pumped. It just happened (Usain's injury). Usain Bolt's name will always live on,\" said Jamaica's first leg Omar McLeod.\n\nThe Chinese team also paid tribute to Bolt who took a bronze in the 100m.\n\n\"I can never imagine such an ending for Bolt. But no matter what ending he had today, he has created so many legends on the track and stays a legend in my heart,\" said Su Bingtian.\n\nBritish anchor runner Nethaneel Michell-Blake also dropped onto the ground, in blissful disbelief as his team took the important victory in a world lead time of 37.47 seconds, beating the American squad, consisting of new 100m winner Justin Gatlin and runner-up Christian Coleman, to second place in 37.52.\n\nJapan took bronze in 38.04. Beijing worlds silver medalists China finished fourth with second-leg runner Xie Zhenye just coming back from injury.\n\n\"We've had a good foundation to build off. After DQs in recent years we knew we had to get the baton round and to finish the night smoothly is a fantastic achievement and we'll enjoy our moment on the podium,\" said Gatlin. The U.S. was disqualified at Beijing 2015 for mishandling of the baton.\n\n\"I trust these guys. Every single one of them puts all the hard work in and they do their business. I mean, the best men won today so credit to GB. They ran a hell of a relay but I think this makes us hungrier. We know what we can do and we'll be ready in 2019,\" he added.\n\nIt was a rollercoaster night for the celebrating home fans when a couple of hours ago their emotion could only be described as disappointed.\n\nFarah failed in his quest for a fourth 5,000m world title in his farewell race just like Bolt as Ethiopian young gun Muktar Edris, 23, seized the glory from the 34-year-old.\n\nThe 2012 world youth champion produced a strong charge on the final stretch as Farah had to struggle out of a siege by three Ethiopians including Yomif Kejelcha, 21, and 17-year-old Selemon Barega, to put on a desperate final sprint but failed to catch up with the leader.\n\n\"I was highly prepared for this race and I knew I was going to beat Mo Farah,\" said Edris.\n\nEdris lifted his first ever major senior world title in 13:32.79, leaving two-time Olympic 5,000 titlist and newly crowned 10,000m winner Farah to second place in 13:33.22. Paul Kipkemoi Chelimo of the United States took bronze in 13:33.30.\n\n\"I gave it everything,\" said Farah who initially curled up on the track in defeat and was pulled up by Edris.\n\n\"It takes so much out of me. Tactically I was trying to cover every move. They had the game plan; one of them was going to sacrifice themselves... and the better man won on the day,\" Farah said.\n\n\"I got boxed in early on - it doesn't normally happen but I got boxed in early and couldn't get out,\" he added.\n\nLike Bolt, Farah would finish his career with an usual feeling of defeat -- he had won this event in the past three world championships and two Olympic Games, together with three world titles and two Olympic gold medals in 10,000m. However, he remains a hero of Britain, bagging one gold and one silver in London.\n\nWhile Farah handed out his long distance crown, the Ethiopians announced their coming.\n\nAlthough missing a podium finish, Kejelcha and this year's U18 3,000m winner Selemon Barega, who placed fourth and fifth respectively, have showed their potential.\n\nSurprises also happened in the field event as Johannes Vetter of Germany grabbed his first ever medal at a major global competition, a gold with his first attempt of 89.89 meters, while defending champion Julius Yego and Olympic champion Thomas Rohler failed to deliver.\n\nJakub Vadlejch of the Czech Republic finished second in 89.73m, ahead of fellow countryman Petr Frydrych on 88.32m.\n\nRohler, from Germany, made a 88.26m throw in his second attempt and finished fourth while Beijing worlds winner Yego was eliminated after the first three rounds.\n\nIn other events, Russia's Maria Lasitskene, competing as an authorized neutral athlete, retained the women's high jump title as the 24-year-old cleared 2.03 meters for the gold medal. Ukraine's Yuliia Levchenko took silver in 2.01 and Poland's Kamila Licwinko was third in 1.99.\n\nLasitskene, who missed last year's Rio Olympics because of Russia's suspension, failed at 1.99 twice but regained form thereafter.\n\n\"My two failed attempts at 1.99m woke me up,\" she said. \"A gold medal here was my main goal for this season but certainly I would like to raise the bar a bit higher. I didn't like any one of my attempts at 2.08m.\" She challenged 2.08 three times but all failed.\n\nRio Olympic champions U.S. team regained the women's 4x100m world crown which they last won at the 2011 Daegu worlds, as they sailed to victory in 41.82 seconds. Britain gladly bagged a silver in 42.12, and defending champions Jamaica clocked 42.19 for the bronze.\n\nIn the women's 100m hurdles, Sally Pearson, who clinched the world title in 2011 and Olympic gold five years ago, clocked 12.59 seconds to win the first gold - and the only medal for Australia at the world championships by far. American Dawn Harper Nelson, who won the Olympic gold in Beijing and silver in London behind Pearson, took silver in 12.63. Germany's Pamela Dutkiewicz finished third in 12.72.\n\n\"It's been a long journey back from injury, but to get this moment and go and celebrate in front of my family is unreal,\" said Pearson, 30. \"This is just so incredible to be a world champion again.\"\n\nRio Olympic silver medalist Kevin Mayer claimed France's second gold from the men's decathlon with a total of 8,768 points. Germany's Rico Freimuth, bronze winner two years ago in the Beijing worlds, took silver in 8,564 points and his compatriot Kai Kazmirek won bronze in 8,488.\n\nCentral delegation visits residents in Inner Mongolia\n\nRescuers continue search in quake-hit Jiuzhaigou\n\nIn pics: magnificent landmarks of BRICS countries\n\nAt least one dead in car crash after violent rally in Virginia, U.S.", "time": "03:20:00"}

"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/athletics/2017/08/13/mo-farah-launches-astonishing-attack-media-trying-destroy/", "body": "In an attack as astonishing as any of his last-lap sprints for gold, Sir Mo Farah has accused the media of trying to \"destroy\" his reputation by misreporting the controversies to have engulfed him.\n\nThe morning after ending his major championship career on the track with a shock defeat in the 5,000 metres, Farah staged a press conference at which his legacy was inevitably the major topic of discussion.\n\nAs was right and proper, he was first asked to reflect upon his unprecedented achievements - 10 successive global titles, including four 5,000m and 10,000m doubles - following his amazing transformation from an also-ran into Britain's most successful track-and-field athlete and an all-time great of distance running.\n\nWhat followed were questions about matters infinitely more in the public interest, and the consequences of them for his legacy, including his ongoing relationship with Alberto Salazar - still under investigation for alleged drugs offences - his links with Jama Aden - arrested last year in connection with a doping inquiry - and evidence he had been given medication that endangered his health.\n\nMo Farah reclaims the 'Mobot' on top of the London Eye 01:24\n\nNot mentioned were his two missed drugs tests before the 2012 Olympics, the failure of a British Athletics doctor to properly record his use of a restricted substance before the 2014 London Marathon, and documents leaked just last month in which he was named as \"likely doping\" before being cleared.\n\nThe 34-year-old, who the media have never accused of cheating, all but branded reports of these facts as fake news, saying: \"It's like a broken record, repeating myself. Why bring it up year after year, making it into headlines? I've achieved what I have achieved - you're trying to destroy it.\"\n\nHe added: \"You can write what you like. The fact is I've achieved what I have from hard work, putting my balls on the line, year after year and delivering for my country.\n\n\"There's nothing else to be said. History doesn't lie. I find it bizarre how certain people write certain things to suit how they want to sell the story.\n\nSir Mo Farah gets emotional after his 5,000m race 01:01\n\n\"Sometimes, you guys get to me - you never write the facts. The fact is, over the years, I have achieved a lot through hard work and pain. If I have crossed the line - 'Mo Farah has done something wrong' - then prove it.\"\n\nFarah was in no doubt how he saw his legacy, one of a Somalian refugee who repaid his adopted homeland with some of the greatest sporting feats in its history.\n\n\"I've done my country and many people proud,\" said Farah, who began his morning by performing his iconic 'Mobot' while perched atop one of the capsules on the London Eye.\n\n\"It makes me proud to be British, to put British distance running on the map.\n\n\"Growing up in Teddington and seeing the Kenyans and Ethiopians winning, I never thought, 'One day, we'll be able to challenge them and beat them at their own game'.\n\n\"I hope I can leave that legacy behind - and get behind younger British kids and see what we can do.\n\n\"It will take 10-15 years to get the next best distance runner in terms of winning medals. But we need to start somewhere.\"\n\nAfter two final farewell races on the track, Farah will switch to the road in a bid to end Britain's long wait for a male marathon champion.\n\n\"I don't like to keep still,\" he said. \"I want to continue on. I like the pain and the challenges of being an athlete. I think I can do something on the road. But I think it will take a few years and few marathons to get it right.\"\n\nRevealing he wanted to be known as Mohamed rather than Mo in future, he added: \"My road name is Mohamed and I just feel like Mo is done. I need to forget about what I've achieved and what I've done.\"\n\nFarah refused to be drawn on whether Salazar, who denies breaking anti-doping rules, would be part of that future, with the American conspicuous by his absence from London 2017.\n\n\"I haven't thought that far ahead,\" Farah said. \"I've a few races left, then I'll take a nice break and see how it goes.\"\n\nHe added: \"Either way, if he was here or not here, day after day, I'd still be putting my balls on the line.\"\n\nWith the questions he clearly did not like out of the way, the conversation switched to Farah's desire to pass on his experience to the next generation. But he could not resist a parting shot at those he accused of being out to get him.\n\n\"Over the years, you guys have done many things to build a person up and bring them back down,\" he said.\n\nBeating his chest, he added: \"The reality is, no matter what you do, I'm going to still keep fighting, keep working, making my country proud.\n\n\"I'm proud to be British and put my GB vest on and do it for my country. You can write what you like but, at the same time, I'm a clean athlete. I sleep well at night, hugging my kids, loving my kids, and showing them what's right. And that's all that counts.\"", "time": "14:00:00"}

"https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/other-sports/why-ultimate-winning-machine-mo-farah-has-become-one-of-the-greats-a3609721.html", "body": "Can we have some more please? It's the question we ask of all great performers in sport. We know you're great but do you think you could try to be a bit greater? It's the right question but it doesn't always get the right answer.\n\nIt's why Usain Bolt lost the other day. He was already as great as any sporting performer in history but what if he could be even greater? So he tried and he lost and lost nothing of his greatness... oh, all right, maybe a little.\n\nHow much greater can Mo Farah be? He won a brutal 10,000metres at the World Championships a few days ago -- tomorrow night he runs in the final of the 5,000m. He won both those events at the last two Olympic Games; only Lasse Viren has done that. He has gone from the Olympic Games to win the same distance double at the next World Championships; only Kenenisa Bekele has done that. Pretty fancy company, then.\n\nIn fact he has done the double at the last two World Championships and is half way to the hat-trick. If he pulls it off, it will be an unprecedented quintuple-double. Pretty fancy numbers.\n\nHow much greater do you want him to be? How much greater is it possible for an athlete to be?\n\nLord Coe said it wasn't enough. He'd like Farah to do another year on the track and devote himself to the pursuit of world records. That would \"close his CV once and for all,\" Coe said.\n\nNice idea, but Farah, now 34, plans devote the next few years to road racing. Coe's words will leave a sting, though, because he wasn't a bad track-runner himself and once set three world records in 41 days -- and also because Farah isn't close to the world record at either of his chosen distances.\n\nBut in distance running, setting world records is an entirely separate discipline to winning gold medals. If you win the Olympic 100m, you're never going to be far off the world record; the tactical 100m final has yet to be run. But if you want to set a world record for the 5k or the 10k, you do it outside the major championships, in a set-piece with pacemakers and a hefty financial incentive.\n\nAttempt a world record at a major championship and you lose. You just set the race up for someone else. You become one of those classic British fourth-place martyrs: heroic front-runners mercilessly picked off in the last 200m. Paula Radcliffe was just such a one, before she converted gloriously to the marathon; so for that matter was Farah, until he took up with his coach Alberto Salazar in 2011.\n\nUnder Salazar, Farah got physically stronger, better able to last a punishing pace with something in reserve and better able to stand the buffets and stumbles that are part of every crowded race. He worked on his finish, eradicating a tendency to overstride as he kicked for home.\n\nIn short, he made himself a perfect machine for winning. Never by much: always by enough, with a surge at 600 metres that brings despair to all but the finest and a kick at 150 that forces the finest to settle for second best. Not a speedster but a racer: a head-to-head man who loves the\n\nbrutalities of chess on the move in spiked footwear and relishes the who-blinks-first intensities of the duel.\n\nThat's where Farah's greatness as a runner operates: not in innocent visions of speed and perfection but down in the dirt, revelling in the struggle, committed to the idea that first is first and second is nowhere.\n\nWe saw every bit of that in the 10,000m last week, which Farah won in his fastest time for six years. The race involved a ferocious attempt to run the finish out of Farah and he responded by repeatedly floating up to the leaders, not to gain a place or two but to tell the leaders: I've got your number -- and you're not fast enough.\n\nBefore the final of the coxless pair at the 1996 Olympic Games, other crews were dreaming of at last beating the dominant pairing of Steve Redgrave and Matthew Pinsent. Before the start, Redgrave growled into Pinsent's ear: \"Let's crush some dreams.\"\n\nThey all dreamed of beating Farah in the 10K, so Farah's tactics were to tell them that he, too, is in the dream-crushing business. And at the finish -- tight, but not all that tight -- Farah was doing what he does best. Finishing a in front of all the others.\n\nSo how great is he? The greatest British runner of all time? You can seek objectivity by counting medals and records but, ultimately, it's one of those personal things. Can you do anything greater than redefine human possibilities, as Roger Bannister did when he ran the first sub-four-minute mile? Or tell a greater story of hope than Kelly\n\nHolmes, coming good at 35 to win the double Coe never managed?\n\nIn the end, such discussions are not about greatness but how you define it. When I was in the Olympic Stadium in London in 2012 and thousands of British people were cheering their guts out for a former Somali refugee named Mohammed -- well, it seemed that sport didn't get a lot greater.\n\nFive years on, much has changed in British life but at least we're still cheering for\n\nSir Mohamed Muktar Jama Farah: as great a British athlete as ever pulled on a pair of spikes.", "time": "12:36:00"}

"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/aug/11/mo-farah-5000-metres-world-athletics-championships", "body": "Whatever happens when Mo Farah steps on to the track for the final time at a major championships on Saturday night, he will leave it knowing no British athlete has been so staggeringly successful - or had their achievements so forcibly questioned. As he put it to one interrogator last month, when asked again about the continuing United States Anti-Doping Agency investigation into his coach, Alberto Salazar: \"It is getting boring now.\"\n\nWinning, however, is something Farah will never grow weary of. When he surged clear to take 10,000m gold last week it was his 11th consecutive world or Olympic title, going back to 2011. That is a remarkable record - especially when you consider his global dominance began only a few months shy of his 29th birthday.\n\nYet the steady supply of gold medals has never made him complacent. The bookmakers make him the overwhelming favourite for the 5,000m but he sees dangers lurking everywhere, and particularly from the Ethiopian trio of Yomif Kejelcha, Muktar Edris and Selemon Barega, and from Paul Chelimo, the American who ran him close during last year's Olympic final. \"I want to leave on a high but it is going to be tough,\" he said. \"There are a lot more guys in the 5,000m and a lot more decisions to be made in a shorter race.\n\n\"In the 10,000m you've got 25 laps so you can relax a little bit if you're further back. In the 5,000m, if you're not there at a certain point, or if someone's going to do something and you're not there, that's it - it's gone.\"\n\nFarah admitted this last big track race will be emotional but he is careful these days not to reveal too much of himself. The persistent drizzle of accusations about Salazar and his relationship with the controversial Somali coach Jama Aden, as well as the leak of some of his athlete biological passport data by the Russian hackers Fancy Bears, have made him more watchful and less carefree - at least in public.\n\nThose who know him well insist he is still the same athlete who once upon a time jumped off bridges for a bet and occasionally got into mischief. Certainly Farah, who was born in Somalia and moved to Britain when he was eight, has not forgotten how fortunate his journey has been.\n\n\"I think I'm a very lucky person in life,\" he said. \"I have a gift not many people have - to be able to know who I was and where I came from as a youngster. I don't think there's enough words to explain the journey and everything. But you have to appreciate what you have and do the best that I can. That's what I was taught in my early years. To appreciate it.\"\n\nHe had a simple answer when asked what - apart from hard work and luck - had kept him on top. \"To be honest, it is about staying hungry, staying humble, being nice, being normal, being who you are,\" he said. \"No one is going to change me.\"\n\nHis four Olympic gold medals were dedicated to each of his children. This one, he wants for his whole family. \"They are everything to me,\" he said. \"I love my four kids and I love my wife. They've been there through ups and downs throughout my career. If I'm going to close in London I wanted them to be a part of it to celebrate with me. That's what we do - we do everything together.\"\n\nFarah will soon have more time to spend with them. He has only two more races left on the track after London, in Birmingham next Sunday and in Zurich four days later - where he hopes to set a personal best over 5,000m - and then he will leave it all behind to become a pure road racer. According to track and field's rumour mill a one- or two-year deal with the London Marathon is also in the pipeline, although suggestions he will leave Salazar and form a new coaching team with the UK Athletics performance director, Neil Black, and the head of endurance, Barry Fudge, have been dismissed by all parties.\n\nIn the past Farah hinted at the prospect of running in the marathon at the Tokyo Olympics. Yet given his first attempt over 26.2 miles in 2014 was a modest 2:08.21 - over a minute outside Steve Jones's British record - there are some wise heads who would not be shocked by a return to the track in time for the 10,000m at the 2019 world championships.\n\nThat assumes, of course, his body holds up - and that he can still crank out a sub-50sec 400m in training, which is his personal barometer that he is in gold medal shape. Given he will be 36 in 2019, you would assume it would be beyond him. But, as his opponents have learned, Farah has a way of defying expectations.", "time": "21:00:00"}

Kejelcha yet comfortably inside the top five without busting a gut.\n\nMo Farah has sealed his place in the final of the 5,000m at the World Championships\n\nThere had been questions over the condition of his left knee after the attrition of his gold-medal run on Saturday, but there seemed to be no after effects in his pursuit of a seventh world title, his fourth at this distance.\n\nThe 34-year-old said: 'It was cold and miserable out there. But it's job done.\n\n'It's been five days of just chilling out and trying to recover. The 10k did take it out of me. I was a little bit beaten up. I'm OK now and glad I've come through. "http://www.china.org.cn/sports/2017-08/13/content_41399789.htm", "body": "The London World Championships just can't stop popping up surprises which could hardly be pleasant memories for Jamaican great Usain Bolt and home hero Mohamed Farah who both bid farewell to their careers.\n\nIn his last race of his career, Bolt limped off the track while hosts Britain took the stunning 4x100m victory to the ecstacy of the capacity London Stadium spectators, a never better redemption for the disappointing silver in the men's 5,000m.\n\nBolt, running the anchor leg, staggered halfway down the straight, dropping the baton before falling facing down. Dreaming of hanging up his running spikes as \"unbeatable\", the 11-time world champion and 8-time Olympic titlist limped across the finish line.\n\nBritish anchor runner Nethaneel Michell-Blake also dropped onto the ground, in blissful disbelief as his team took the important victory in world lead time of 37.47 seconds, beating the American squad, consisting of new 100m winner Justin Gatlin and runner-up Christian Coleman to the second place in 37.52. Japan took bronze in 38.04.\n\nBeijing worlds silver medalists China finished fourth with second-leg runner Xie Zhenye just coming back from injury.\n\nIt has been a rollercoaster night for the celebrating home fans when a couple of hours ago their emotion could only be described as disappointed.\n\nFarah failed in his quest for a fourth 5,000m world title in his farewell race just like Bolt as Ethiopian young gun Muktar Edris, 23, seized the glory from the 34-year-old.\n\n2012 world youth champion Edris produced a strong charge on the final stretch as Farah had to struggle out of the surrounding of Edris' fellow countrymen Yomif Kejelcha, 21, and 17-year-old Selemon Barega to put on a desperate final sprint but failed to catch up with the leader.\n\nEdris lifted his first ever major senior world title in 13:32.79, leaving two-time Olympic 5,000 titlist and newly crowned 10,000m winner Farah to the second place in 13:33.22. Paul Kipkemoi Chelimo of the United States took bronze in 13:33.30.\n\n\"I gave it everything,\" said Farah who initially curled up on the track in defeat and then was pulled up by Edris.\n\nLike Bolt, Farah would finish his career with an usual feeling of defeat -- he had won this event in the past three world championships and two Olympic Games, together with three world titles and two Olympic gold medals in 10,000m. However, he remains hero of the country, bagging one gold and one silver in London.\n\nWhile Farah handed out his long distance crown, the Ethiopians announced their coming.\n\nAlthough missing a podium finish, Kejelcha and this year's U18 3,000m winner Selemon Barega, who placed fourth and fifth respectively, have showed their potential.\n\nThe surpris also happened in the field event as Johannes Vetter of Germany grabbed his first ever medal at a major global competition, a golden one with his first attempt of 89.89 meters in javelin while defending champion Julius Yego and Olympic champion Thomas Rohler failed to deliver.\n\nJakub Vadlejch of Czech Republic finished second in 89.73m ahead of fellow countryman Petr Frydrych with 88.32m.\n\nRohler, from Germany, made a 88.26m throw in his second attempt and finished fourth while Beijing worlds winner Yego was eliminated after the first three rounds.\n\nIn other events, Russia's Maria Lasitskene, competing as the authorized neutral athlete, retained the women's high jump title as the 24-year-old cleared 2.03 meters for the gold medal. Ukraine's Yuliia Levchenko took silver in 2.01 and Poland's Kamila Licwinko was third in 1.99.\n\nLasitskene, who missed last year's Rio Olympics because of Russia's suspension, failed at 1.99 twice but regained form thereafter.\n\n\"My two failed attempts at 1.99m woke me up,\" she said. \"A gold medal here was my main goal for this season but certainly I would like to raise the bar a bit higher. I didn't like any one of my attempts at 2.08m.\" She challenged 2.08 three times but all failed.\n\nRio Olympic champions U.S. team regained the women's 4x100m world crown which last won at 2011 Daegu worlds as they sailed to victory in 41.82 seconds while hosts Britain gladly bagged a silver in 42.12. Defending champions Jamaica clocked 42.19 for the bronze.\n\nIn the women's 100m hurdles, Sally Pearson, who clinched the world title in 2011 and Olympic gold five years ago, clocked 12.59 seconds to win the first gold and only medal for Australia at the world championships by far. American Dawn Harper Nelson, who won the Olympic gold in Beijing and silver in London behind Pearson, took silver in 12.63. Germany's Pamela Dutkiewicz finished third in 12.72.\n\n\"It's been a long journey back from injury, but to get this moment and go and celebrate in front of my family is unreal,\" said Pearson, 30. \"This is just so incredible to be a world champion again.\"\n\nRio Olympic silver medalist Kevin Mayer claimed France's second gold from the men's decathlon with a total of 8,768 points. end his track era at the end of the month to focus on the marathon and goes for gold in the 5,000m at the World Championships in London on Saturday.\n\nFarah has won Great Britain's sole gold medal of the championships - the 10,000m on the first day - and is aiming to mount a double defence of the titles he won in 2013 and 2015.\n\nAnd the four-time Olympic champion is ready to close a chapter which has also brought six world titles and five European crowns.\n\nHe said: \"Yeah it is emotional but it has been a long career. You guys have seen me since I was a child, running around, going to the English Schools. To come this far has been incredible.\n\n\"To be honest, what is keeping me on the top, it is about staying hungry, staying humble, being nice, being normal, being who you are. No one is going to change me.\"\n\nHis family joined him on the track after his 10,000m title win last Friday - the scene where he won the 5,000m and 10,000m at London 2012 - and he wants his four children and wife Tania to be part of his send-off.\n\nHe said: \"My family is everything to me. I love my kids and love my wife. They've been there through ups and downs throughout my career. If I'm going to close in London I wanted them to be a part of it to celebrate with me.\n\n\"That's what we do - we do everything together. For me, when I took my kids to the track that was beautiful. Five years ago who would have thought that the twins in mummy's tummy would be on the track?\n\n\"I think I'm a very lucky person in life. I have a gift that not many people have - to be able to know who I was and where I came from as a youngster.\n\n\"To have achieved what I have achieved has been incredible. I don't think there's enough words to explain the journey and everything. But you have to appreciate what you have and do the best that I can. That's what I was taught in my early years. Appreciate it.\"\n\nFarah will run in the Diamond League in Birmingham next Sunday before a final track race at the Diamond League final in Zurich on August 24.\n\nBut he is focused on the World Championships as he prepares to start the countdown to his marathon career.\n\n\"I want to leave on a high because that's the perfect note. do it one mo' time? He's won every world or Olympic 5,000- and 10,000-meter title since the 5K at the 2011 world championships. Before every title defense, people offer theories about how to beat Farah, and either those tactics aren't tried, or they are, and fail. Farah says this will be his last global title race on the track, so between that and his competing in front of an adoring home crowd, somebody better have something special in store to unseat him.\n\nAny challenge is likely to come from a strong Ethiopian trio. Muktar Edris has the best time in the world this year, but he'll need to do something more than simply run fast to get rid of Farah. Yomif Kejelcha has challenged Farah a few times, and has a great kick, but he too will have to go above and beyond past attempts to win.\n\nThe wild card is Selemon Barega, who is reportedly 17 years old. He's won two world junior titles -- one just last month -- and joined the select sub-13:00 club this summer. In races like the men's 400-meter hurdles and women's 400 at this meet, rapidly improving youngsters have shocked big-name veterans with fearless why-the-heck-not racing. Barega might be bold enough to figure that it's time for Farah, who's twice his age, to make way for the new wave.\n\nAmerican Paul Chelimo won the Olympic silver medal behind Farah last summer. He had a rough qualifying race -- a few shoving incidents as well as a fall -- and might not be as fresh as he'd like. He's gutsy enough to go with any big move to break Farah early, and can also finish well. The other American, Ryan Hill, has a great kick, and will finish highest in a race where others let it come down to the last lap and a half.\n\nRELATED: How to Watch Track & Field\n\nWomen's (4:30 p.m. Eastern) and Men's (4:50 p.m.) 4 x 100-meter relays: If he's true to his word, this race will be Usain Bolt's last in a championship meet. Thanks in part to Bolt's unmatchable anchor legs, Jamaican men have won the last six global titles (four world championships, two Olympics). They also hold the world record.\n\nIn the 20th century, American men dominated this event, but they've struggled in recent years with dropped batons, botched handoffs, and other snafus that have either kept them from medaling in the final or, often, even reaching the final. The U.S. squad got the silver at Worlds four years ago, their only medal in the event since winning in 2007. Guys, just get the baton around the track, okay?\n\nThe U.S. women have done much better at keeping cool under pressure. They have the last two Olympic titles, but were beaten by Jamaica in the last two world championships. A big question for this year's U.S. prospects is the health of 100-meter champ Tori Bowie. She fell hard at the end of that race and withdrew from the 200.\n\nRW IN YOUR INBOX: Have the latest news, advice, and inspiration sent to you every day with our Runner's World Newsletters.\n\nWomen's 100-meter hurdles (3:05 p.m. Eastern): This event was a U.S. sweep at last year's Olympics. The 2012 Olympic champion, Sally Pearson of Australia, is resurgent this year, with the second fastest time behind Harrison. "http://www.telegraph.co.uk/athletics/2017/08/12/without-world-title-cannot-call-mo-farah-legend-sport/", "body": "I first came across Mo Farah when he was still fairly fresh-faced and new to the senior ranks at the 2006 European Championships in Gothenburg.\n\nHe had been a strong junior and a good under-23 athlete, but at that stage he was just bouncing along and probably not really hitting his maximum potential. Up to that point he had never won a senior international medal, but he grabbed silver in the 5,000\u2009metres and made it to the World Championships final a year later.\n\nBack then he was just a cheeky chap having a bit of fun. We are both huge Arsenal fans so we shared some banter over that and, like a lot of endurance runners, he was typically easy-going.\n\nWho would have thought that he'd go from my team-mate winning a first European silver to being on the verge of 11 successive global distance titles? I certainly never expected him to reach the dizzy heights of a four-time Olympic champion and if you asked him honestly, I imagine he would probably have said the same as well.\n\nIt's a shame that he is leaving the track after these World Championships because he has shown that he is still good enough to win medals on the biggest stage.The 5,000m looks like it will be tougher than the 10,000m last week, but it's impossible to predict anything other than a victory, which would be the perfect send-off for him.\n\nMo Farah's career so far - in 60 seconds 01:03\n\nWhen you come to the end of your career, people start assessing what you have achieved and the impact you have had. Will Farah ever truly be regarded as a legend of the sport? I don't think he can be, because he's never broken one of the major world records.\n\nThat is something that has eluded him and it is vital to being deemed a legend. Usain Bolt is undoubtedly a legend because he has broken so many records, in addition to winning gold medals. Farah, on the other hand, is certainly one of the great athletes, but I don't think it is possible to classify him as a legend because he hasn't broken the records that his predecessors set.\n\nFarah's career is always going to be clouded in some level of controversy because of his coach and his training partners. Maybe the general public won't really care about those things and they don't particularly want to know about it - they just want to support their hero.\n\nIt is a shame for Farah, but I do remain unsure of the situation with his coach.\n\nDoing things like not speaking openly before the World Championships doesn't help Farah either. Everyone else did it, so why shouldn't he? British Athletics wanted him to speak, but he - or the PR company that he hires - chose not to.\n\nI don't doubt him because I do think he has integrity.\n\nI haven't really had much contact with him over the past six years since I retired, but the person that I knew before had full integrity and was honest in what he did.\n\nSo I have to believe that is the case now. What is certain is that his success has done a lot for the sport in Britain. He's brought back a sense of excitement that there was in the early 1980s with the likes of Seb Coe and Steve Ovett.\n\nOur long-distance running is starting to rebuild and Mo's presence is bringing more fans to it. I'm sure a lot of them are fans of Farah rather than fans of the sport, but he has brought them to athletics tracks and hopefully they will stay once he has gone.\n\nThere is no doubt he has done our sport proud and I'd like to see him win one more medal for Britain tonight.\n\nIf he does that and doubles our medal tally in London it will be fantastic.", "time": "07:16:00"}

"label": {"eng": "Yomif Kejelcha"}, "score": 3, "type": "wiki", "id": "1417608"}], "url": "http://english.sina.com/news/2017-08-13/detail-ifyixcaw4481340.shtml", "body": "LONDON, Aug. 12 (Xinhua) -- The London World Championships just can't stop popping up surprises which could hardly be pleasant memories for Jamaican great Usain Bolt and home hero Mohamed Farah who both bid farewell to their careers.\n\nIn his last race of his career, Bolt limped off the track while hosts Britain took the stunning 4x100m victory to the ecstacy of the capacity London Stadium spectators, a never better redemption for the disappointing silver in the men's 5,000m.\n\nBolt, running the anchor leg, staggered halfway down the straight, dropping the baton before falling facing down. Dreaming of hanging up his running spikes as \"unbeatable\", the 11-time world champion and 8-time Olympic titlist limped across the finish line.\n\nBritish anchor runner Nethaneel Michell-Blake also dropped onto the ground, in blissful disbelief as his team took the important victory in world lead time of 37.47 seconds, beating the American squad, consisting of new 100m winner Justin Gatlin and runner-up Christian Coleman to the second place in 37.52. Japan took bronze in 38.04.\n\nBeijing worlds silver medalists China finished fourth with second-leg runner Xie Zhenye just coming back from injury.\n\nIt has been a rollercoaster night for the celebrating home fans when a couple of hours ago their emotion could only be described as disappointed.\n\nFarah failed in his quest for a fourth 5,000m world title in his farewell race just like Bolt as Ethiopian young gun Muktar Edris, 23, seized the glory from the 34-year-old.\n\n2012 world youth champion Edris produced a strong charge on the final stretch as Farah had to struggle out of the surrounding of Edris' fellow countrymen Yomif Kejelcha, 21, and 17-year-old Selemon Barega to put on a desperate final sprint but failed to catch up with the leader.\n\nEdris lifted his first ever major senior world title in 13:32.79, leaving two-time Olympic 5,000 titlist and newly crowned 10,000m winner Farah to the second place in 13:33.22. Paul Kipkemoi Chelimo of the United States took bronze in 13:33.30.\n\n\"I gave it everything,\" said Farah who initially curled up on the track in defeat and then was pulled up by Edris.\n\nLike Bolt, Farah would finish his career with an usual feeling of defeat -- he had won this event in the past three world championships and two Olympic Games, together with three world titles and two Olympic gold medals in 10,000m. However, he remains hero of the country, bagging one gold and one silver in London.\n\nWhile Farah handed out his long distance crown, the Ethiopians announced their coming.\n\nAlthough missing a podium finish, Kejelcha and this year's U18 3,000m winner Selemon Barega, who placed fourth and fifth respectively, have showed their potential.\n\nThe surpris also happened in the field event as Johannes Vetter of Germany grabbed his first ever medal at a major global competition, a golden one with his first attempt of 89.89 meters in javelin while defending champion Julius Yego and Olympic champion Thomas Rohler failed to deliver.\n\nJakub Vadlejch of Czech Republic finished second in 89.73m ahead of fellow countryman Petr Frydrych with 88.32m.\n\nRohler, from Germany, made a 88.26m throw in his second attempt and finished fourth while Beijing worlds winner Yego was eliminated after the first three rounds.\n\nIn other events, Russia's Maria Lasitskene, competing as the authorized neutral athlete, retained the women's high jump title as the 24-year-old cleared 2.03 meters for the gold medal. Ukraine's Yuliia Levchenko took silver in 2.01 and Poland's Kamila Licwinko was third in 1.99.\n\nLasitskene, who missed last year's Rio Olympics because of Russia's suspension, failed at 1.99 twice but regained form thereafter.\n\n\"My two failed attempts at 1.99m woke me up,\" she said. \"A gold medal here was my main goal for this season but certainly I would like to raise the bar a bit higher. I didn't like any one of my attempts at 2.08m.\" She challenged 2.08 three times but all failed.\n\nRio Olympic champions U.S. team regained the women's 4x100m world crown which last won at 2011 Daegu worlds as they sailed to victory in 41.82 seconds while hosts Britain gladly bagged a silver in 42.12. Defending champions Jamaica clocked 42.19 for the bronze.\n\nIn the women's 100m hurdles, Sally Pearson, who clinched the world title in 2011 and Olympic gold five years ago, clocked 12.59 seconds to win the first gold and only medal for Australia at the world championships by far. American Dawn Harper Nelson, who won the Olympic gold in Beijing and silver in London behind Pearson, took silver in 12.63. Germany's Pamela Dutkiewicz finished third in 12.72.\n\n\"It's been a long journey back from injury, but to get this moment and go and celebrate in front of my family is unreal,\" said Pearson, 30. \"This is just so incredible to be a world champion again.\"\n\nRio Olympic silver medalist Kevin Mayer claimed France's second gold from the men's decathlon with a total of 8,768 points. Germany's Rico Freimuth, bronze winner two years ago in the Beijing worlds, took silver in 8,564 points and his compatriot Kai Kazmirek won bronze in 8,488.\n\nCentral delegation visits residents in Inner Mongolia\n\nIn pics: magnificent landmarks of BRICS countries\n\nLocal community organizes donation event to aid Jiuzhaigou in Hefei\n\nSilk Road Chinese Ethno Music Festival held in Pula, Croatia", "time": "23:08:00"}

out on a fairytale finale at the World Championships. And this morning he waved farewell to track athletics in Britain in the most dramatic of fashion - atop the London Eye.\n\nThe four-time Olympic champion failed to mount a third defence of his 5,000m title as Ethiopia's Muktar Edris claimed gold in London on Saturday. Edris even had the audacity to celebrate with a 'Mobot' inside London Stadium.\n\nFarah, though, reclaimed his iconic pose by climbing to the very top of the London Eye on a bright, crisp morning and producing a 'Mobot' to the whole capital.\n\nFarah, who had already won the 10,000m last week, had not lost a final in 2,176 days.\n\nThe 34-year-old collapsed to the track after the race and covered his face before being hauled to his feet.\n\nHe is due to retire from the track at the end of the month, after the Diamond League final in Zurich, to focus on the marathon, and conceded he was overcome in the London Stadium.\n\nHe said: \"I had tears in my eyes, I've never had that before. It's been an amazing journey. To end it in London, where it all started, I got a bit emotional.\n\n\"I look at my family, what I've done and it gets to you. At the end of the day I'm human and it hasn't all been a smooth ride.\n\n\"If I had it perfect it would have been nice to end in double double but anything is possible. At some point it has to come to an end.\n\n\"I always told myself London is where it started and London was where it was going to stop. I was known as normal Mo and then overnight after London I was 'Mo', I couldn't go anywhere. To finish here is a nice thing.\n\n\"I know myself when I crossed the line there was nothing left of me, nothing. I gave my all. "http://www.eurosport.co.uk/athletics/no-golden-ending-as-farah-signs-off-with-worlds-silver_sto6286530/story.shtml", "body": "Mo Farah gritted his teeth and went to the well one last time. But roared on and implored on by an expectant crowd it was not to be.\n\nAnd that, quite simply, is sport, fairytale endings, as we've learned so spectacularly in recent days, don't come as standard.\n\nFarah narrowly missed out on a remarkable fifth consecutive major championships distance double in London but don't say he settled for silver. Farah isn't the sort to settle for anything.\n\nIt had been 2176 days since his last defeat on the track in a major championship final. In that time he'd won four Olympic, six world and three European titles. He had secured his place in the pantheon of his sport and the hearts of his nation.\n\nBut in the end time - and his rivals - simply caught up with the greatest track athlete Britain has ever produced.\n\nPerhaps the exertions of his brilliant win in the World Championship 10,000m took their toll as the 34-year old couldn't respond to the late injection of pace from Ethiopia's Muktar Edris - whose tactics were straight out the Farah playbook and who secured the world 5,000m title.\n\nBut while the gold dream faded, Farah didn't. Beaten but not down, he kicked again on the home straight to snatch silver ahead of the USA's Paul Chelimo while team-mate Andrew Butchart finished eighth.\n\nHe will have two more races on the track, in Birmingham and Zurich, before he sets his sights on the road, but his place in history is long secure.\n\n\"I gave it my all, I had nothing left,\" he said.\n\n\"The 10,000m took a lot more out of me than I had realised. They had a game plan and that was that one was going to sacrifice themselves, but I gave it my all.\n\n\"I didn't have a single thing left to give at the end. I got boxed in and couldn't get out.\n\n\"I remember in 2008, being so disappointed and not sure whether to carry on with the sport or not. I had to decide what it took to become a champion and that was to move to the other side of the world. Nothing was guaranteed but I took that chance.\n\n\"I have a few more races on the track and then I will take a short break and then this chapter of my life is closed. It's a very special night. It's been amazing but it's been a long journey. It didn't quite hit home until I took a few moments to myself where I realised this is it.\"\n\nElsewhere, Katarina Johnson-Thompson certainly salvaged some pride - but fell just short of her medal ambition with a fifth place in the women's high jump final.\n\nThe British record holder equalled her season's best with a 1.95 metre effort but couldn't get over 1.97m, which would have been just a centimetre under her personal best from last year's Rio Olympics.\n\nHowever, in a high-quality final, the 24-year old would have needed to jump higher than she ever has before to make the podium.\n\nRussia's Maria Lasitskene, competing as a neutral athlete, defended her title with a clearance of 2.03m while Ukraine's Yuliia Levchenko took silver ahead of Poland's Kamila Licwinko. Johnson-Thompson's British team-mate Morgan Lake finished sixth.\n\n\"It was close but not close enough but when I reflect I've got to be happy with that in my first-ever high jump final,\" she said.\n\n\"I felt pretty fatigued in the warm-up and my legs are pretty tired. It's been a long week but I'm not making excuses. "http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/sport-others/does-mo-farah-leave-the-track-as-greatest-distance-man-4794585/", "body": "By: Reuters | Published:August 13, 2017 10:39 am Mo Farah has never been down that route, with his capacity for really fast times never examined. (Source: Reuters) Toilet Ek Prem Katha box office collection day 2: Akshay Kumar's film expected to rake in the moolah on SaturdayGo where you feel secure, RSS's Indresh Kumar tells Hamid AnsariAishwarya Rai Bachchan steals a million hearts in this white Manish Malhotra suit at IIFM\n\nRight at the last, Mo Farah's unbeatable air could not stand up to another examination by the world's best distance runners as he was denied one final global triumph in his farewell championship track race on Saturday.\n\nAs the Briton was consoled - and congratulated on a peerless track career - by his competitors following his world 5,000 metres silver in the stadium where his legend was first properly sculpted in 2012, the only question that remained was where he stands in the annals of track distance running.\n\nThere is a powerful argument to say, after 10 straight global championship victories stretching back to the 2011 world 5,000 metres triumph in Daegu, that the 34-year-old is the greatest distance racer we have ever seen on the track.\n\nDespite his defeat on Saturday, his ability, time and again, to fend off every challenge and tactic thrown at him -- from Ethiopian and Kenyan athletes ganging up on him to being spiked and bruised in physical races - and still sprint to victory was unprecedented during an incredible six-year reign.\n\nHis ability to strike for home with that long, loping stride, anywhere from 600 metres to 100 metres out - and then to find yet another gear when it seemed as if he was flat out - marked him as a unique talent.\n\nYet being considered the best racer is very different from being seen as the greatest distance athlete of all-time.\n\nSebastian Coe, the IAAF President and a massive fan of Farah, set the ball rolling when declaring in Friday's Evening Standard newspaper that Haile Gebrselassie was the greatest.\n\n\"When it comes to the debate on the greatest distance runner of all time, I'm tough on this,\" said Coe, who himself is in the shake-up for the title best middle-distance runner of them all.\n\n\"For me, it's not Mo Farah -- and that's not to do a disservice to Mo, who is one of the greats of all time. \"For me that still has to be Haile Gebrselassie, for the distances that he covered, the titles he won and the world records he broke.\"\n\nBOTH DISTANCES\n\nIn championship running, Farah won 10 on the trot before Saturday's setback, compared with Gebrselassie's six in a row at 10,000 metres and Kenenisa Bekele's best run of four championship wins in succession at both distances.\n\nYet the two Ethiopian greats also went chasing records to extraordinary effect, Bekele setting a total of three new world marks at 5,000m and 10,000m and Gebrselassie seven at the two events.\n\nFarah has never been down that route, with his capacity for really fast times never examined.\n\nIt remains an extraordinary fact that the most successful championship runner ever at 5,000m with five global titles, is ranked only the 31st-fastest runner of all time, at 12 minutes 53.11 seconds. Bekele holds the world record at 12:37.35.\n\nAt 10,000 metres, in which Farah has also won a record five global golds, he is also still only the 16th-fastest (26:46.57), nearly half a minute down on Bekele's world record of 26:17.53.\n\nBekele, a year older than Farah at 35, won nine global golds, once went unbeaten for eight years at 10,000 metres, won 11 world cross-country titles and now holds the second-fastest marathon time in history (2 hours 3 minutes 3 seconds).\n\nFor the moment, even if Gebrselassie was the great Ethiopian trailblazer, it seems fair to rank Bekele the highest for his all-round achievements on the track, country and roads.\n\nYet Farah, who has run only one marathon, finishing eighth in London in 2014 in a relatively modest 2:08:21, believes he can make a big impact on the roads.\n\nThe most amazing tale in the annals of British athletics may not quite have run its course yet.\n\nAs Farah, who admitted to being tearful after an amotional night, said after his race: \"As I'm getting older, it's getting a bit more challenging and that's the reason I'm going to end on the track and see what I can do on the roads.\n\n\"This is end of in terms of major championships, I'm done. I've closed that chapter of my life. I want to start a new challenge in my life.\"\n\nFor all the latest Sports News, download Indian Express App", "time": "05:21:00"}

"body": "LONDON (Reuters) - Right at the last, Mo Farah's unbeatable air could not stand up to another examination by the world's best distance runners as he was denied one final global triumph in his farewell championship track race on Saturday.\n\nAs the Briton was consoled - and congratulated on a peerless track career - by his competitors following his world 5,000 metres silver in the stadium where his legend was first properly sculpted in 2012, the only question that remained was where he stands in the annals of track distance running.\n\nThere is a powerful argument to say, after 10 straight global championship victories stretching back to the 2011 world 5,000 metres triumph in Daegu, that the 34-year-old is the greatest distance racer we have ever seen on the track.\n\nDespite his defeat on Saturday, his ability, time and again, to fend off every challenge and tactic thrown at him -- from Ethiopian and Kenyan athletes ganging up on him to being spiked and bruised in physical races - and still sprint to victory was unprecedented during an incredible six-year reign.\n\nHis ability to strike for home with that long, loping stride, anywhere from 600 metres to 100 metres out - and then to find yet another gear when it seemed as if he was flat out - marked him as a unique talent.\n\nYet being considered the best racer is very different from being seen as the greatest distance athlete of all-time.\n\nSebastian Coe, the IAAF President and a massive fan of Farah, set the ball rolling when declaring in Friday's Evening Standard newspaper that Haile Gebrselassie was the greatest.\n\n\"When it comes to the debate on the greatest distance runner of all time, I'm tough on this,\" said Coe, who himself is in the shake-up for the title best middle-distance runner of them all.\n\n\"For me, it's not Mo Farah -- and that's not to do a disservice to Mo, who is one of the greats of all time.\n\n\"For me that still has to be Haile Gebrselassie, for the distances that he covered, the titles he won and the world records he broke.\"\n\nBOTH DISTANCES\n\nIn championship running, Farah won 10 on the trot before Saturday's setback, compared with Gebrselassie's six in a row at 10,000 metres and Kenenisa Bekele's best run of four championship wins in succession at both distances.\n\nYet the two Ethiopian greats also went chasing records to extraordinary effect, Bekele setting a total of three new world marks at 5,000m and 10,000m and Gebrselassie seven at the two events.\n\nFarah has never been down that route, with his capacity for really fast times never examined.\n\nIt remains an extraordinary fact that the most successful championship runner ever at 5,000m with five global titles, is ranked only the 31st-fastest runner of all time, at 12 minutes 53.11 seconds. Bekele holds the world record at 12:37.35.\n\nAt 10,000 metres, in which Farah has also won a record five global golds, he is also still only the 16th-fastest (26:46.57), nearly half a minute down on Bekele's world record of 26:17.53.\n\nBekele, a year older than Farah at 35, won nine global golds, once went unbeaten for eight years at 10,000 metres, won 11 world cross-country titles and now holds the second-fastest marathon time in history (2 hours 3 minutes 3 seconds).\n\nFor the moment, even if Gebrselassie was the great Ethiopian trailblazer, it seems fair to rank Bekele the highest for his all-round achievements on the track, country and roads.\n\nYet Farah, who has run only one marathon, finishing eighth in London in 2014 in a relatively modest 2:08:21, believes he can make a big impact on the roads.\n\nThe most amazing tale in the annals of British athletics may not quite have run its course yet.\n\nAs Farah, who admitted to being tearful after an emotional night, said after his race: \"As I'm getting older, it's getting a bit more challenging and that's the reason I'm going to end on the track and see what I can do on the roads.\n\n\"This is end of in terms of major championships, I'm done. I've closed that chapter of my life. I want to start a new challenge in my life.\"", "time": "19:24:00"}

Farah with The Mobot Simon Rice for Metro.co.ukSaturday 12 Aug 2017 9:18 pm Share this article with Facebook Share this article with Twitter Share this article with Google Plus Share this article with Whatsapp Share this article through email Share this article through sms\n\nMo Farah had to make do with silver in the 5,000m final as his glittering track career ended in disappointment.\n\nThe Briton had been the strong favourite coming into the race having been unbeaten over the distance since 2011.\n\nMo Farah misses out on golden goodbye as he takes 5,000m silver\n\nHowever he could only look on as Muktar Edris crossed the line in front of him, with the Ethiopian cheekily performing The Mobot as he did.\n\nPeople weren't impressed, with some seeing the celebration as disrespectful to Farah.\n\nHere's how some were reacting on Twitter...\n\nDid that wanker who won do the mobot? absolute disgrace to an all time great! #London2017 #mofarah All time great\n\n-- Mark Cunningham subscribe, try again laterInvalid Email\n\nSir Mo Farah was \"a little beaten up\" after making his way into Saturday's World Championships 5000m final - but it's nothing compared to what he's put himself though to reach this point.\n\nThe 34-year-old was second in Wednesday night's heat in 13 minutes 30.18 seconds and having already won the 10,000m in style has just one more track race at a major championships remaining in his formidable career.\n\nFarah shrugged off a knee injury and a cut leg, having been spiked in the 10km, to negotiate tricky conditions and a field almost universally against him to set up a fitting finale.\n\nHe has the added pressure of carrying the British team as their sole medalist ahead of his planned track retirement later this month.\n\nBut Farah is an athlete who personifies the adage of 'no pain, no gain', and he clearly thrives on pressure, as shown in a film released by Nike showing the lengths to which he goes to be the best.\n\nBehinds the scenes footage from Farah's inner sanctum show what it takes to have the kick over the final 100m that no-one in the world can compete with.\n\nFrom pushing his body to the limit in all weather to ice baths and underwater treadmills.\n\nIt shows the bumps, bruises and blood from all-to-common falls and rep after rep on lonely tracks.\n\nSome of Mo's least glittering moments also feature, such as collapsing and needing oxygen after the New York Half Marathon in 2014, but it ends as usual with his trademark smile.\n\n\"I'm going to do it. You'll see me at the start line. I just have to recover,\" he said ahead of Saturday's 5000m final.\n\n\"I'm cold, it was miserable out there but it's job done. I had to get back into some kind of running again. It's been five days of chilling out and recovering.\n\n\"The 10k did take a lot out of me and I'm a little beaten up but I'm okay. The knee's alright, the body is a bit tired - that's all.\n\n\"The doctors and the team have been great for me. In fact I went home to stay in Teddington, that's where my family are, and I was like, 'Nah, I need to get back in the hotel'. I only stayed one night.\"\n\nFarah is wary of the risk of disappointing his home crowd on Saturday, especially after retiring Usain Bolt managed just bronze in the 100m.\n\n\"You've seen it with Usain Bolt, it happens. No-one is going to give it to you - no matter who you are, even Usain Bolt,\" he said.\n\n\"Those boys are coming for me, they are hungry. "http://www.firstpost.com/sports/iaaf-world-athletics-championships-2017-mo-farah-retires-as-undisputed-legend-despite-bittersweet-end-to-career-3925775.html", "body": "London: Briton Mo Farah departs an undisputed legend of the track in terms of titles won, but to many his association with coach Alberto Salazar will forever cast a unwanted pall on his career.\n\nThe 34-year-old Somalia-born champion stuck with Salazar despite serious allegations against him which he strenuously denied and have never been proven, but refuse to go away.\n\nA dejected Mo Farah after finishing second in the Men's 5000m. AP\n\nHowever, the contrast to the universal adoration showered on fellow legend Usain Bolt who also bid farewell to championship racing is stark.\n\nFarah certainly got cheered to the rafters when he won his two Olympic and world gold and silver medals in London and has been ennobled by Queen Elizabeth II in recognition of his achievements.\n\nBut despite the plethora of golds and breaking up the hegemony of the Kenyans and Ethiopians in the events, a real barometer of his popular standing in the United Kingdom is reflected by the BBC Sports Personality of the Year award which is voted on by the public.\n\nOn only one occasion, in 2011, has he reached the top three, something British triathlon great Alistair Brownlee put down to him not being considered British.\n\n\"It's really sad, because for me he is the perfect British story,\" Brownlee told The Guardian last December.\n\n\"It's what we should be about: a person who comes to Britain as a young man, as a refugee, and an ex\u2011schoolteacher (Alan Watkinson) identifies something that he's brilliant at and he represents Britain as the best in the world.\"\n\nFarah shrugs off the constant snubs saying he always gets a great reception from the crowds at the British meetings.\n\nHe rightly points out his voyage from war-torn Somalia to arriving in England, via a spell with his grandparents in Djibouti, with his mother Amran and two of his five siblings (brothers Ahmed and Wahib but not his twin Hassan who was too ill to travel and they would not see each other for 12 years) as an eight-year-old boy and his subsequent success is what will remain with him.\n\n\"Just knowing where I grew up, where I come from, the journey I have taken,\" he told The Sun last year.\n\n'A new world'\n\nFarah, whose mother brought him and his siblings to join their father Muktar who is an IT consultant but divorced soon afterwards leaving for Brighton with Farah's two brothers, for his part found England a beguiling place.\n\n\"I remember walking in, and the doors opened, and there were escalators,\" he told The Big Issue magazine.\n\n\"It was fascinating for me as a child. A new world -- like when I went to Disneyland. And for me, it was where my family was, so it was home.\"\n\nHis mum though was the parent that Farah -- who had to live with his aunt Kinsi when they settled in England -- felt closest to, a similarity he shares with Bolt who also described himself as a 'mummy's boy'.\n\n\"I was always a happy kid, up for laughs, joking around,\" said Farah, who makes a show of running to his wife Tania and their four children -- including twin girls Aisha and Amani -- at the end of finals.\n\n\"And I always had that cheeky smile.\n\n\"If I was causing trouble I could get away with it because of that. I used it on my mum quite a lot. I was a lot closer to my mum than my dad. I'm a mummy's boy really.\"\n\nIf there is a dream to realise as he winds down his career it is to spend more time with Hassan and he described movingly in his biography what it meant when he finally was reunited with him in 2003.\n\n\"It felt like a part of me had been missing the whole time I had been growing up separately from Hassan.\n\n\"At last, the void in my life was gone.\"\n\nThe void he leaves in track distance running is immeasurable.\n\nPublished Date: Aug 13, 2017 02:55 pm | Updated Date: Aug 13, 2017 02:56 pm\n\nTags :#Alberto salazar#Alistair brownlee#Athletics#England#Great britain#Iaaf world championships 2017#London#Mo farah#Usain bolt", "time": "09:58:00"}

"body": "Right at the last, Mo Farah's unbeatable air could not stand up to another examination by the world's best distance runners as he was denied one final global triumph in his farewell championship track race on Saturday.\n\nAs the Briton was consoled -- and congratulated on a peerless track career -- by his competitors following his world 5,000 metres silver in the stadium where his legend was first properly sculpted in 2012, the only question that remained was where he stands in the annals of track distance running.\n\nThere is a powerful argument to say, after 10 straight global championship victories stretching back to the 2011 world 5,000 metres triumph in Daegu, that the 34-year-old is the greatest distance racer we have ever seen on the track.\n\nDespite his defeat on Saturday, his ability, time and again, to fend off every challenge and tactic thrown at him -- from Ethiopian and Kenyan athletes ganging up on him to being spiked and bruised in physical races -- and still sprint to victory was unprecedented during an incredible six-year reign.\n\nHis ability to strike for home with that long, loping stride, anywhere from 600 metres to 100 metres out -- and then to find yet another gear when it seemed as if he was flat out -- marked him as a unique talent.\n\nYet being considered the best racer is very different from being seen as the greatest distance athlete of all-time.\n\nSeb Coe, the president of the IAAF and a massive fan of Farah, set the ball rolling when declaring in Friday's Evening Standard newspaper that Haile Gebrselassie was the greatest.\n\n\"When it comes to the debate on the greatest distance runner of all time, I'm tough on this,\" said Coe, who himself is in the shake-up for the title best middle-distance runner of them all.\n\n\"For me, it's not Mo Farah -- and that's not to do a disservice to Mo, who is one of the greats of all time.\n\n\"For me that still has to be Haile Gebrselassie, for the distances that he covered, the titles he won and the world records he broke.\"\n\nIn championship running, Farah won 10 on the trot before Saturday's setback, compared with Gebrselassie's six in a row at 10,000 metres and Kenenisa Bekele's best run of four championship wins in succession at both distances.\n\nYet the two Ethiopian greats also went chasing records to extraordinary effect, Bekele setting a total of three new world marks at 5,000m and 10,000m and Gebrselassie seven at the two events.\n\nFarah has never been down that route, with his capacity for really fast times never examined.\n\nIt remains an extraordinary fact that the most successful championship runner ever at 5,000m with five global titles, is ranked only the 31st-fastest runner of all time, at 12 minutes 53.11 seconds. Bekele holds the world record at 12:37.35.\n\nAt 10,000 metres, in which Farah has also won a record five global golds, he is also still only the 16th-fastest (26:46.57), nearly half a minute down on Bekele's world record of 26:17.53.\n\nBekele, a year older than Farah at 35, won nine global golds, once went unbeaten for eight years at 10,000 metres, won 11 world cross-country titles and now holds the second-fastest marathon time in history (2 hours 3 minutes 3 seconds).\n\nFor the moment, even if Gebrselassie was the great Ethiopian trailblazer, it seems fair to rank Bekele the highest for his all-round achievements on the track, country and roads.\n\nYet Farah, who has run only one marathon, finishing eighth in London in 2014 in a relatively modest 2:08:21, believes he can make a big impact on the roads.\n\nThe most amazing tale in the annals of British athletics may not quite have run its course yet.\n\n(This article has not been edited by DNA's editorial team and is auto-generated from an agency feed.)", "time": "21:27:00"}

Championships was delivered on Saturday night thanks to the women's 4x100m relay team.\n\nAsha Philip, Desiree Henry, Dina Asher-Smith and Daryll Neita won silver with a superb run of 42.12.\n\n5,000m "709359"}], "url": "http://www.firstpost.com/sports/iaaf-world-athletics-championships-2017-medal-tally-usa-continue-to-lead-as-usain-bolt-mo-farah-falter-in-farewell-3925179.html", "body": "London: Usain Bolt's final track appearance ended with pain and frustration on Saturday as he pulled up injured running the final leg of the World Championships 4x100 metres relay as Britain stunned the United States to win a shock gold medal.\n\nBolt, who had to settle for bronze in the individual 100 metres, had been hoping to sign off from the sport by leading Jamaica to a fifth successive world relay title but they were struggling in a distant third place when he collected the baton.\n\nJamaica's Usain Bolt grimaces after injuring himself during the men's 4x100m final. AP\n\nMeanwhile, Maria Lasitskene became the first Russian to win a gold medal at the World Championships in London after successfully defending her high jump title on Saturday.\n\nThe 24-year-old, competing as an authorised neutral athlete, stretched her unbeaten streak to 25 competitions by clearing 2.03 metres to triumph in the London Stadium.\n\nAnother athlete who couldn't close out his career on a high was Mo Farah, whose aura of invincibility after six years of unrelenting success was finally cracked in his very last major track race on Saturday as he lost his world 5,000 metres title to Ethiopia's Muktar Edris.\n\nSeeking a fitting end to his matchless long-distance racing career before moving to marathon running, the 34-year-old Briton's bid for a fifth straight global 10,000/5,000m double was scuppered as he had to settle for the silver.\n\nYet even in defeat, Farah demonstrated his champion's spirit as he fought back in the dying metres when it looked as if he would be shut out of the medals completely.\n\nIn a thrilling finale featuring four athletes careering towards the line, Farah snatched back second place behind Edris, who clocked 13 minutes 32.79 seconds after a searing final lap of 52.6 seconds.\n\n\"I gave it all but I had nothing left at the end,\" a crestfallen and emotional Farah said.\n\nIn 4x100 metres women's relay, Tori Bowie anchored the United States to victory in the women's 4x100 metres relay at the World Championships on Saturday.\n\nIt was the sixth time the US have won the event and the gold was a record 15th World Championship medal for Allyson Felix, who ran the second leg.\n\nWe are on top of the world,\" Bowie said. \"I am grateful to be able to run and bring these ladies home to the gold. It has been a mixed week but two gold medals is amazing for me.\"\n\nBowie was shadowed all the way to the line by Briton Daryll Neita who led her team to silver, in 42.12, ahead of 2015 champions Jamaica who were missing their usual anchor runner in Shelly-Ann Fraser-Pryce.\n\nIn men's javelin, Johannes Vetter made up for just missing out on an Olympic medal last year when the he won the javelin at the World Athletics Championships on Saturday as his great rival and Olympic champion Thomas Roehler finished off the podium.\n\nCzech Republic pair Jakub Vadlejch, coached by world record holder Jan Zelezny, and Petr Frydrych threw personal bests of 89.73 and 88.32 metres respectively to take silver and bronze.\n\nVetter's opening throw of 89.89 was enough to win the gold and the 24-year-old was overcome with emotion after clinching the title which was confirmed after Vadlejch's last throw.\n\nHere is the IAAF World Athletics Championships 2017 medal tally after Day 9\n\nRank
